<SECOND>AM-Klansmen-Pleas,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Four Former Klansmen Plead Guilty In 1979 Clash With Marchers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four former Ku Klux Klan members entered
guilty pleas in federal court Monday for their part in a violent
clash in 1979 with black marchers.
   The four were the last of nine former Klan members who were
indicted and eventually pleaded guilty to federal charges stemming
from the gunfire in a Decatur parade that wounded several people.
   There were no fatal injuries in the 1979 confrontation. The
wounded included police officers.
   Two of the former Klansmen _ Ray Winford Steele and William
Riccio _ pleaded guilty Monday to a felony count of obstruction of
justice and a misdemeanor count of conspiring to violate civil
rights.
   The other two _ William Johnny Mason and Lynwood White _ pleaded
guilty to the misdemeanor conspiracy count.
   The former Klansmen were accused of blocking a Southern Christian
Leadership Conference march on May 26, 1979. The marchers were
protesting the prosecution of a mentally retarded black man charged
with the rape of a white woman in Decatur.
   The misdemeanor conspiracy count carries a maximum sentence of
one year in prison and a $1,000 fine. The felony count carries a
maximum penalty of five years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
   U.S. District Judge John Hancock delayed sentencing for up to a
month.
</TEXT>
