<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--SkydivingDeaths     01-09 0127</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Skydiving Deaths,0133</SECOND>
<HEAD>Instructor, Student Die in Skydiving Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A skydiving instructor and his student plunged more
than 9,000 feet to their deaths after their parachutes failed to
open, authorities said.
   Sunday's deaths of Donald Batchelor, 34, and Zaine Oller, were
under investigation, authorities said.
   Batchelor, a skydiving instructor with 10 years' experience, was
strapped to Oller's back in a formation in which the instructor
holds the controls to their common harness and parachute, Metro-Dade
police spokeswoman Lucy Fitts said.
   A reserve parachute also failed to open, authorities said.
   The victims were the last of five passengers to jump out of a
plane that took off from Homestead General Aviation Airport in
southwest Dade County, Ms. Fitts said.
   Oller's age was not available.
</TEXT>
