<HEAD>Court to Decide Bankruptcy Issue in Connecticut Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether states generally are immune from being sued for money
damages by bankruptcy trustees.
   The court said it will use two cases of bankrupt businesses in
Connecticut to determine whether states, and possibly the federal
government also, enjoy such immunity.
   The justices will hear an appeal by Martin W. Hoffman, a
court-appointed trustee supervising payment to creditors of
Willington Convalescent Home Inc. and Edward Zera, who ran a
maintenance service.
   The nursing home, which shut down in April 1983, said Connecticut
officials owed it $64,010 in Medicaid payments for patients treated
at the home.
   Zera, who declared bankruptcy in 1983, sought to recover $2,100
in taxes paid to Connecticut.
   Hoffman invoked federal bankruptcy law to recover the money in
behalf of the nursing home and Zera and use it to help pay their
creditors.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last June that the
immunity from money damages states generally enjoy extends to
federal bankruptcy law.
   The Reagan administration said it agrees with the 2nd Circuit
court ruling, but urged the Supreme Court to hear arguments in the
case because other federal appeals courts have taken an opposite
view.
   Such disputes arise frequently and the conflict should be
resolved by the high court, the Justice Department said.
   The department said the reasoning of the 2nd Circuit court
appears to apply to federal agencies as well as to states.
   The Supreme Court is expected to announce a decision by July.
   The case is Hoffman vs. Connecticut, 88-412.
</TEXT>
