<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-FosterCare     01-09 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Foster Care,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Ruling in Maryland Foster Care Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling that
expands the right of allegedly abused or mistreated foster children
to sue their social workers.
   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that workers may
be sued for damages under a key federal civil rights law by foster
children in federally funded programs.
   The court rejected an appeal by Maryland social service employees
seeking greater legal protection.
   The Reagan administration joined in urging the court to review a
ruling by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. Justice Department
lawyers said the appeals court ruling would expose thousands of
state and local social welfare workers to personal financial
liability for injuries suffered by children in foster homes.
   The government said the appeals court ruling could have even more
far-reaching impact if it is extended to apply to other federally
funded social welfare programs.
   State and local workers who administer Aid for Dependent
Children, Medicaid and food stamp programs also could be exposed to
the risk of big-money damages, the government said.
   The Maryland case stems from a suit against 21 officials,
caseworkers and supervisors who help administer the state's
federally funded foster care program in Baltimore.
   They were sued by children who say they were victims of physical
and sexual abuse and medical neglect.
   A federal judge ordered officials to submit a plan for improving
conditions in foster homes, and for at least monthly monitoring of
the placement of children in the homes.
   The judge also required the officials to improve medical services
for foster children and to report instances of poor medical care to
the children's attorneys.
   The judge also ruled that social workers who place or keep
children in foster homes are not entitled to immunity from lawsuits
in such cases.
   The 4th Circuit court upheld the decision in February 1988.
   The appeals court rejected the social workers' claims that a
federal law providing funds for foster care created no duty on their
part to know whether a child would be exposed to mistreatment or
abuse.
   The appeals court said the social workers' right to claim
immunity from suit must be based on more than their own belief that
they acted properly. It is up to a trial court examining the facts
to decide whether the social workers permitted mistreatment, the
appeals court said.
   The National Association of Social Workers, in supporting the
appeal by the Maryland employees, said the 4th Circuit court ruling
places social workers at risk for alleged abuses that occurred
decades earlier.
   ``No professional consensus exists even now'' on how to assure
foster children will not be harmed, the association said.
``Maltreatment of children in foster homes often is difficult, and
at times impossible, to prevent by even a very highly skilled and
well-trained social worker.''
   The Supreme Court already is studying a related issue in the case
of a Wisconsin boy who suffered severe beatings by his father.
   In that case, the justices are expected to decide whether public
officials may be sued when their alleged gross negligence permits a
child to be abused by a parent.
   Social workers were accused of failing to come to the aid of the
boy even after they had evidence that he was beaten repeatedly.
   The case acted on today focuses on whether a federal civil rights
law enacted after the Civil War permits damage suits based on
alleged violations of a 1980 law, the Adoption Assistance and Child
Welfare Act.
   The 1980 law requires states to meet certain conditions before
receiving federal funds for foster care. The 4th Circuit court said
the 1980 law creates a basis for private citizens to sue if those
conditions allegedly are not met.
   The case is Massinga vs. L.J., 87-1796.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
