<SECOND>PM-Vegas Earthquake,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquakes Rattle Las Vegas, Aleutian Islands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake shook the Las Vegas
area, cracking some windows and rattling nerves, but authorities
received no reports of serious damage or injury.
   ``My kid came in the living room screaming that his bed was
moving,'' said Adam Churchin, who lives four miles southeast of
downtown Las Vegas. ``It scared the living daylights out of him.''
   The temblor, centered 10 miles northeast of Las Vegas, struck at
9:08 p.m. Sunday and measured between 3.2 and 3.5 on the Richter
scale, according to seismologists at the U.S. Geological Survey
offices in Menlo Park, Calif., and Boulder, Colo.
   Earlier Sunday, the Alaksa Tsunami Warning Center reported two
moderate earthquakes in an area southeast of Adak in the Aleutian
Islands. The quakes registered 5.6 and 4.8 on the Richter scale, but
neither was felt at Adak, the nearest populated area.
   The Las Vegas quake was felt most strongly in suburban North Las
Vegas, where a Police Department switchboard operator reported
receiving at least 500 telephone calls from worried citizens.
   Some callers, including Municipal Court Judge Gary Davis,
reported cracked windows, but there were no reports of serious
property damage or injuries, according to the operator, who declined
to identify herself.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude, or the height of quake-generated shock waves recorded
on a seismograph.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
