<HEAD>Court to Rule on Double Jeopardy in Missouri Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to use the case
of a convicted murderer from Missouri to study double-jeopardy
protection for criminal defendants.
   The court agreed to hear arguments by state officials seeking to
reinstate a life prison sentence for Larry P. Thomas.
   Thomas was convicted of murder and attempted robbery in an
attempted holdup of an auto parts store in St. Louis on Nov. 8, 1972.
   Mentoe Vernell, a customer at the store, died in a shootout with
Thomas.
   Thomas was sentenced to 15 years in prison for attempted robbery
and a life term for murder.
   Then-Gov. Christopher Bond of Missouri commuted the robbery
sentence in 1981 after Thomas had served about eight years. He
remained in prison on the murder conviction.
   A state court subsequently threw out the sentence for attempted
robbery and credited the time Thomas had served for that crime to
the murder sentence. The state courts said he must continue serving
the life sentence.
   Thomas then appealed in federal court to have the murder sentence
thrown out.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in a 5-4 ruling last
April, ruled that Thomas' right against double jeopardy was violated
because he was given multiple sentences for the same crime. The
governor's commutation means that Thomas legally had served one of
his sentences and must be set free, the appeals court said.
   ``We hold that Thomas had legally satisfied the 15-year sentence
for the attempted robbery and that his continued confinement for the
felony murder offense violated his double jeopardy rights,'' the
appeals court said.
   State officials, in appealing to the Supreme Court, said the
appeals court exceeded its authority and misinterpreted Missouri law.
   The state attorney general's office said the state courts
``cured'' the double jeopardy violation when it threw out the
sentence for attempted robbery and gave Thomas credit for time
served.
   The case is Jones vs. Thomas, 88-420.
</TEXT>
