<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Strike     01-09 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Strike,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Strands Commuters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transport workers walked off the job to
protest the arrest of six union leaders, and thousands of commuters
across the country were stranded, police said Monday.
   More than 30,000 buses, vans, trucks and other vehicles making up
two-thirds of the nation's public transport system halted services
Sunday, said a police official on condition of anonymity.
   At least 200 people were injured slightly by strikers who threw
stones at buses that did not observe the stoppage, said the official.
   The strike followed the arrests Saturday of union leaders accused
of instigating violence during agitation to demand the shifting of a
bus terminal from a northern suburb of Dhaka to the city center,
according to the official.
   Protesters also demanded an end to what they called forcible
collection of illegal tolls, which they said went to the ruling
Jatiya Party.
</TEXT>
