<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Libya 1stLd-Writethru a0606 01-09 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0606,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Urges Restaint After Libya Incident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with French speech, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France told the Security Council today that
all parties should show restraint following the U.S. downing of two
Libyan MiGs over the Mediterranean Sea last week.
   ``We hope everyone will exercise restraint and refrain from any
act which could enhance tensions,'' said French envoy Pierre
Brochand, the deputy permanent representative.
   Brochand spoke at an emergency session convened to discuss
Libya's demand that the United States be condemned for shooting down
the planes Wednesday.
   The United States said the planes were armed and dangerous. Libya
said they were unarmed and on a reconnaissance mission.
   France, the first U.S. ally to speak in the debate, did not
support or criticize either side and is expected to abstain when the
Security Council votes on the issue, probably Wednesday.
   Also speaking today were Finland, Ethiopia, Senegal, Sudan,
India, Morocco and Bangladesh. The session then adjourned until
Tuesday, when a resolution was expected to be submitted.
   Except for France, major U.S. allies like Britain have not spoken
and virtually all speakers have denounced or criticized the U.S.
action.
   ``France deeply regrets the incident between Libyan and U.S. air
forces,'' Brochand said. ``Our country, which borders the
Mediterranean, is particularly concerned about the maintenance of
stability and peace in that region.''
   Finnish Ambassador Klaus Tornudd also urged restraint. He noted
that Libya said its aircraft were on routine reconnaissance and the
United States said its planes were on a routine training mission.
   ``There must be something wrong with the routines if this is the
result,'' he said.
   He said there was a need for an international code of conduct
covering international naval forces and aircraft.
   On Friday, U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters exhibited two
enlarged photographs that he said proved the Libyan warplanes were
armed with missiles. Libya called the photographs fabrications.
   U.S. officials said the two photographs showed one of the two
Libyan aircraft. Blurred spots were under the wings and on the
fuselage, and the United States said the spots indicate missiles.
   The Soviet Union and other nations said the photographs were too
blurred to prove the planes were armed.
   Last week, 17 speakers, mostly Arab and developing nations,
condemned the U.S. action as premeditated aggression.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze, speaking to
reporters today in Paris, said he told Secretary of State George
Shultz that ``the most important thing is to stabilize the situation
after the air incident.''
   Shevardnadze and Shultz have been in Paris for an international
conference on chemical weapons.
   Earlier, Soviet Ambassador Alexander M. Belonogov, the permanent
U.N. representative, deplored the U.S. action in the Mediterranean
and said it hurt possibilities for Middle East peace.
   The United States and Britain are expected to veto any resolution
criticizing the U.S. action. The five permanent members with veto
power can kill any resolution on the 15-member council.
   The other permanent members are China, France and the Soviet
Union.
</TEXT>
