<FIRST>r i AM-NaziFiles     01-09 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nazi Files,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Convicted in Nazi Documents Theft From U.S.-run Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court on Monday convicted a former employee of a
U.S.-run Nazi document center for his role in the theft of thousands
of files from the facility.
   The court sentenced Alfred Darko, former head of the center's
photographic department, to two years and four months in prison.
Three other defendants _ all Germans _ also were convicted and given
suspended sentences.
   Darko, a native of the Ivory Coast, was found guilty of stealing
4,000 Nazi files and selling them to dealers for up to $22,000.
   Chief judge Clemens Basdorf did not order Darko to prison
immediately. Darko, who has spent nine months in investigative
custody and who is reported to be in ill health, was ordered not to
leave West Berlin and to report to police once a week.
   Basdorf said Darko was not the only employee suspected in the
thefts, but he added that Darko had refused to identify individuals
he said stole the documents.
   ``Darko knows the truth, but we don't know why he will not name
the accomplices,'' Basdorf said.
   More than 10,000 documents are believed to be missing from the
center.
   The Berlin Document Center contains 30 million Nazi files seized
by the Allies after World War II. Among the documents are personnel
files of prominent Nazis and an almost complete list of Nazi Party
members.
   The thefts were discovered last year.
   Among the documents stolen was the personnel file of former
Gestapo officer Klaus Barbie, known as the Butcher of Lyon, who is
serving a life sentence in France for war crimes.
   A marriage request by SS officer Adolf Eichmann was also among
the documents stolen. Eichmann was executed in Israel after being
convicted of playing a major role in the Nazi deportation and murder
of millions of Jews.
   The court on Monday also found three other men guilty.
   A Hamburg military documents dealer, Andre Huesken, was sentenced
to two years' probation and fined $27,000 for selling many of the
documents to clients around the world.
   Two West Berlin antique dealers, Alfred Borrmann and Henry
Berger, also were given suspended sentences and fined for their
roles in delivering and selling the documents to dealers and
collectors.
</TEXT>
