<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--YouthFestival     01-09 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Youth Festival,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Building 150,000-Seat Stadium for World Festival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea has nearly finished a 150,000-seat
stadium in Pyongyang, one of the facilities for the 13th World
Festival of Youth and Students in July, an official report said
Monday.
   The Korean Central News Agency, monitored in Tokyo, said the
Rungrado Stadium will be used for the festival's opening and closing
ceremonies.
   Communist and Third World nations join in the festival, a major
political, arts and sports event held every four years. The last
festival was held in Moscow in 1985.
   Other facilities being expanded or refurbished are Pyongyang
International Airport, Tumangang Railway Station, Nampo Port, as
well as traffic, communications and welfare service facilities, and
parks and recreation grounds, it said.
   North Korea has said the festival will be ``magnificent in
scale'' and will follow the theme of ``anti-imperialist solidarity,
peace and friendship.''
</TEXT>
