<FIRST>r i AM-WolfPrize     01-09 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wolf Prize,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two U.S. Mathmeticians Awarded Israel's Wolf Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1989 Wolf Foundation Prize in mathematics
was awarded to two Americans for their work in theoretical
mathematics and geometry, the foundation announced Monday.
   The $100,000 prize is to be shared by Alberto P. Calderon of the
University of Chicago and John W. Milnor of Princeton University.
   Calderon, born in Mendoza, Argentina, was cited for his
``groundbreaking work'' on differential equations, the foundation
said.
   Milnor, of Orange, N.J., was selected for his ``highly original
discoveries in geometry which have opened important new vistas,'' it
said.
   The prizes will be presented to Calderon and Milnor in May by
President Chaim Herzog.
   The privately run Wolf Foundation grants six annual awards of
$100,000 each in the fields of physics, chemistry, medicine,
agriculture, mathematics and the arts. The other prizes are to be
announced later.
   The $12 million foundation was established in 1975 by Dr. Ricardo
Wolf, a German-born chemist and diplomat who emigrated to Cuba and
in 1961 became Cuba's ambassador to Israel. He lived in Israel until
his death in 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
