<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Sweden-Poland     01-09 0110</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Sweden-Poland,0112</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Tourists Flood Sweden with Black Market Caviar, Vodka</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish tourists sold $1 million in
vodka, Russian champagne and caviar on the black market in Sweden
last year, a newspaper reported Monday.
   The smuggled goods sold in the southern port city of Malmo last
year averaged up to $200 for each of the 50,000 Polish tourists who
visited the city, according to the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet. The
goods also included crab, ham, clothes, crystal and amber worth $170
to $200.
   Police inspector Jonte Sterup was quoted as saying the Poles used
most of the money to buy U.S. dollars before they return home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
