<FIRST>u a AM-Poll-Homeless Bjt   01-09 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poll-Homeless, Bjt,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Support for Higher Taxes To Combat Homelessness</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY27</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six in 10 Americans say homelessness afflicts
their own communities, and a majority would pay higher federal taxes
to help ease the problem, a Media General-Associated Press poll has
found.
   The national survey found wide agreement that homelessness is a
serious and worsening problem and general dissatisfaction with the
level of the federal government's response.
   Sixty percent of the respondents favored more federal spending
for the homeless, with nearly all in that group saying they would
pay higher taxes for that purpose.
   Accordingly, respondents rated the problem as extraordinarily
severe. Sixty-eight percent called it ``very serious'' and 24
percent said ``fairly serious.''
   The poll also exhibited the broad reach of homelessness:
Three-quarters said the problem plagues communities of all sizes,
not just big cities, and 59 percent said there were homeless people
in their own communities.
   The telephone survey, conducted among 1,084 randomly selected
adults Nov. 10-20, had a margin of error of plus or minus three
percentage points.
   The poll was completed before the holiday season and winter cold
refocused attention on the homeless. Still, 68 percent said
homelessness was worsening, just a quarter said it was unchanged and
a scant 3 percent saw improvement.
   A plurality said homelessness is primarily society's fault,
rather than the fault of the homeless themselves. Approaches such as
more housing for the homeless and subsidized apartments for the poor
won strong support.
   Views were divided on who is responsible for solutions. A 32
percent plurality said the federal government was chiefly
responsible for helping homeless people; 24 percent said state
governments; 18 percent said local governments; and 9 percent said
private charities. The rest had no opinion.
   Wherever prime responsibility lies, only 27 percent said the
federal government does enough to prevent people from becoming
homeless, and 58 percent said it does not. The remaining 15 percent
had no answer.
   Of the 60 percent who favored increasing federal spending on
programs for the homeless, 86 percent said they would be willing to
pay higher taxes for that purpose. Overall, 52 percent said they
would pay more to help the homeless.
   On specific programs, 62 percent said the federal government
should spend more on housing for the homeless, and 65 percent
favored the preventive measure of building more federally-subsidized
housing.
   Majorities of all groups favored subsidized housing, including
those least likely to support federal spending _ Republicans and
conservatives. In virtually all measures, however, homelessness was
seen as a problem by greater shares of women, Democrats, liberals,
minorities, lower-income respondents and younger people. They also
were more apt to blame society and to favor a broader federal
response.
   For example, 78 percent of women rated the problem as ``very
serious,'' compared with 56 percent of men. Eighty-three percent of
Democrats said it was getting worse, compared with 54 percent of
Republicans. And sixty-four percent of liberals said society was at
fault, compared with 37 percent of conservatives.
   Of those with family incomes under $25,000 a year, 73 percent
favored more subsidized housing for the poor; of those earning more
than $50,000, just 54 percent agreed.
   Respondents were divided on whether homeless people should be
allowed to live on the streets. Fifty-one percent said people should
not be allowed to live on the streets if they want to, but 45
percent said they should have that right.
   On the root cause of homelessness, 45 percent said society mainly
is at fault and 33 percent said the homeless themselves are chiefly
to blame. The rest, 22 percent, had no answer.
   Media General Inc., a communications company based in Richmond,
Va., publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News
Leader, the Tampa (Fla.) Tribune and the Winston-Salem (N.C.)
Journal, and operates TV stations WXFL in Tampa, WCBD in Charleston,
S.C., and WJKS in Jacksonville, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
