<FIRST>r i AM-IrishNewspaper     01-09 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish Newspaper,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oldest Newspaper to be Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The News Letter, the Belfast
daily that claims to be the world's oldest surviving
English-language newspaper, is to be sold, it was announced Monday.
   The Belfast Telegraph, a Belfast evening paper, said it would buy
the News Letter, its sister weekly the Sunday News, and two other
local free papers.
   The News Letter was founded in September 1737, although its
oldest surviving issue is from March 1738, and it prides itself on
being the first newspaper to report the American Declaration of
Independence on this side of the Atlantic.
   A morning daily since 1855, the paper has a circulation of 43,700
and is the voice of Northern Ireland Unionism _ the preservation of
the province's union with Britain and opposition to uniting the
island under rule from Dublin, capital of the Irish Republic.
   Capt. Bill Henderson, chairman of Century Newspapers, which owns
the News Letter, said the newspaper would remain ``the responsible
voice of Unionism in Ulster'' under the ownership of the
non-partisan Belfast Telegraph.
   Henderson said the company had needed massive capital investment,
new presses and computer systems, and the cost put the future of the
papers in doubt. He said he agreed to sell after the buyer
guaranteed to maintain the News Letter as a Unionist paper and to
invest in its future.
   The sale price was withheld pending government approval.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0124 </DOCNO>
