<FIRST>r i AM-Libya     01-09 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Criticizes Foreign Journalists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya's official news agency on Monday
criticized foreign journalists who reported there were weapons
around the desert factory the United States alleges is a chemical
weapons plant.
   About 100 journalists were expelled from Libya on Sunday, and
about 30 others were told late Sunday that they had to depart Monday.
   They arrived last week after U.S. fighter jets shot down two
Libyan warplanes over the Mediterranean.
   The expulsion orders came a few hours after the journalists were
taken Saturday evening to the plant at Rabta, 60 miles southwest of
Tripoli.
   Libya insists the plant is designed for producing medicine.
   Journalists were not allowed inside the plant, and because it was
nightfall when they arrived by bus, they could see very little from
the outside.
   Clearly visible, however, was a ring of surface-to-air missiles
around the plant, as well as a concrete-based radar station a few
miles away. Libyan officials said the defenses were put into place
after President Reagan last month said he could not rule out a
military strike against the plant.
   Libya's official news agency, JANA, on Monday said the
journalists were invited to see the plant ``as an expression of good
will and out of its concern to enable them to acquaint themselves
with the reality of a small country upon which aggression and
confrontation are imosed by a superpower, namely America.
   ``Statements in some news reports that the mere fact of the
journalists seeing the buildings did not help determine the nature
of these buildings and that there are weapons, guns and buildings
are inaccurate and lack objectivity,'' JANA said. ``The journalists,
unless they are are specially qualified, are not experts in
determining the nature of the factory and its installations.
   ``Adopting the argument of the existence of guns and weapons in
the area surrounding the factory to give it another character falls
in line with the desires of some and the reply to it is: in the face
of the threats of America to deal a blow to the area, are the masses
who are staging a sit-in there not entitled to make available the
means to defend the area and to protect themselves?'' the dispatch
said.
   Libya, it said, ``in so far as it is concerned with enabling
journalists to carry out their professional duties, requires the
necessary commitment to the rules of neutrality, objectivity and
impartiality'' from journalists.
   Libya's foreign minister, in Paris for a conference on chemical
weapons, said Sunday his country had no plans to manufacture
chemical weapons. When asked if Libya planned to make such arms, he
replied: ``You will never know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-People-Sajak     01-09 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Sajak,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vanna-Less Pat Sajak Latest to Take on Carson's Hold as Late Night
King</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Sajak, the ex-local weatherman who rode to
national stardom on ``Wheel of Fortune,'' spins his personal wheel
of fortune tonight as the latest personality to challenge Johnny
Carson as late-night TV king.
   A full-page advertisement in today's Daily Variety industry
newspaper urges TV viewers to tune in ``The Pat Sajak Show,''
imploring: ``Don't go to bed until you turn him on.''
   Sajak, who is staying on with his evening ``Wheel of Fortune''
duties but quitting the daytime version, debuts his 90-minute CBS
talk show with Chevy Chase, Joan Van Ark and Michael Gross slated as
guests.
   Sajak, 42, said he has realistic expectations, adding the network
hasn't given him a ratings goal.
   ``I do know they don't think someone's going to go in there and
knock somebody else off,'' Sajak said. The show goes up against
Carson and the first half of ``Late Night With David Letterman'' on
NBC, and ABC's ``Nightline.''
   ``I would not be surprised if in some back office in this
building someone has said, `Hey look, it may be one year, it may be
two years, it may be five years, but eventually Johnny's going to
leave. And we'll have our little niche. We'll be in good shape,'''
Sajak said.
   Past challengers to NBC's venerable ``The Tonight Show With
Johnny Carson'' have faired poorly. The airwaves have been littered
with victims trying to unseat Carson, including Joan Rivers, Alan
Thicke, Joey Bishop and Dick Cavett.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0143 </DOCNO>
