<FIRST>r w AM-Budget-VeteransAffairs     01-09 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Veterans Affairs,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Slight Increase Asked For Veterans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Monday asked Congress for a
small increase in funding for veterans' medical care and pensions as
he proposed outlays of $29.9 billion for the new Department of
Veterans Affairs.
   Outlays for the Veterans Administration, which provided benefits
and services to veterans for 58 years, are estimated to be $29.2
billion in fiscal 1989. The budget for the new department, which
assumes Cabinet status in March, calls for a $700 million increase.
   Among the budget proposals are a slight increase in outlays for
medical care, including the treatment provided to veterans at
hospitals, nursing homes and on an outpatient basis. In fiscal 1989,
outlays totaled $11.4 billion. The 1990 budget calls for $11.5
billion.
   Outlays for construction of state extended care facilities
increased from $37 million in 1989 to $44 million in 1990 while
outlays for major project construction was cut from $527 million to
$514 million.
   The budget proposes using construction funds for two large
hospital projects in Palm Beach, Fla., and Newington, Conn.
   Proposed outlays for total pensions are $4 billion, a $94 million
increase over the estimated total for fiscal 1989. Veterans age 65
or older with low incomes and wartime-service are entitled to the
pensions. The wartime-service does not differentiate between combat
or non-combat duty.
   The pension payments also included a 4 percent cost-of-living
increase effective this month.
   Total outlays for income security for disabled, aged or deceased
veterans in the 1990 budget are $16.4 billion, up from $15.6 billin
in 1989.
   The Reagan administration, in the budget, also recommends linking
future veterans compensation cost-of-living adjustments to annual
changes in the Consumer Price Index.
   The administration also proposes changes in the veterans housing
program, including orgination fees for participating in federal
credit programs. The budget plan did not specify the cost of the
fees.
   Two other recommendations affecting housing for veterans propose
legislation to increase the expiring fee charged on guaranteed
housing loans and vendee loans and to allow negotiated interest
rates on guaranteed mortgages.
   The expiring fee charge would increase from 1 percent to 3.8
percent of the mortgage amount and the borrower could add the fee to
the mortgage. A vendee loan is a direct loan made to veterans and
non-veterans who purchase property that the Veterans Administration
acquired through defaults.
   The administration also is seeking budget authority of $1.5
million for the court of Veterans Appeals, which would allow
veterans to appeal some benefit decisions of the department's Board
of Veterans' Appeals.
   Facing a major cut are grants for the construction of state
veterans cemeteries, which would be reduced from $5 million in 1989
to $1.9 million in 1990.
   The funding would be used to expand national cemeteries at Fort
Snelling, Minn., and Jefferson Barracks, Mo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Zambia-Riots     01-09 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Zambia-Riots,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rioters Protest Food Subsidy Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested 61 people who rioted
over confusion surrounding a new food subsidy program, officials
said Monday.
   Rioting broke out in the central Zambian town of Luanshya on
Sunday and paramilitary police were dispatched to restore order,
said provincial political secretary Boniface Mapani.
   No further details of the police action were given. Local media
reports said the rioting followed the introduction of a coupon
system to buy corn meal, Zambia's staple food.
   Coupons were not readily available and the program created
``widespread confusion,'' according to the reports.
   The corn meal subsidy program is aimed at reducing state food
subsidies, but so far it has been plagued by coupon shortages and
administrative inefficiency.
   Under the program, eligible families receive free coupons to help
them buy corn meal at state-designated shops. It replaces a broader
subsidy program that was scrapped in response to demands by the
International Monetary Fund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Religious     01-09 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Religious,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Approves Soccer Stadium That Ultra-Orthodox Jews Oppose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Supreme Court on Monday cleared the way
for construction of a soccer stadium in Jerusalem, a move opposed by
ultra-Orthodox Jews who fear weekend games will desecrate the
Sabbath.
   The ruling, which orders the Interior Ministry to sign the
building permit, ended a 15-year battle to get the athletic field
built, according to the office of Jerusalem Mayor Teddy Kollek.
   Kollek hailed the decision as a victory for Jerusalem's youth,
who must travel to the coastal city of Jaffa to see Betar Jerusalem,
the team with the largest following.
   Kollek, along with liberal parliament member Dedi Zucker and a
group of sports fans, filed the petition to the high court a year
and a half ago.
   ``I share the happiness of the residents and sports fans of the
capital,'' Kollek said in a statement.
   He said the stadium would be built ``as soon as possible,''
adding: ``September's soccer season will open in a new stadium.''
   Construction has been blocked by the Interior Ministry, which
refused to sign the building permit despite approval for the arena
from all necessary local government and planning authorities.
   The ministry, which traditionally is headed by an Orthodox
minister, argued that noise from the stadium and its parking lot
could disrupt religious Jews on the Sabbath, which begins at sundown
Friday and continues until sundown Saturday.
   The religious also argued that building the stadium would
encourage Jews to break the Sabbath by driving to see games.
   Most soccer games in Israel are played on Saturday.
   Interior Ministry Spokeswoman Tova Elinson said there would be no
comment on the ruling until the minister, Arye Deri, returned from
the United States on Tuesday.
   The 12,000-seat stadium is to be built in the Malha neighborhood
in southwestern Jerusalem. Many residents of the Bayit Vagan
neighborhood to the north are Orthodox Jews.
   The site has a grass playing field but no seating and no parking
facilities. Construction is expected to cost about $24 million.
   Zucker, a member of the left-leaning Citizens Rights Party,
described the ruling as a victory for secular Jews. He noted 18
months ago ``we opened the town for theaters and movies on Fridays,
and now we have given the town what it is entitled to have, like any
other city in Israel, a stadium.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1433EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-History     01-09 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-History,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Archive Opens 500,000 Pre-revolutionary Files</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Central State Archive has opened 500,000 secret
files on such subjects as the Russian Orthodox Church and the White
Guard opposition to Bolshevik Revolution, Tass said Monday.
   Records on organizations ``liquidated'' during the 1920s and
1930s, at the height of the Stalinist repression, are being
declassified, the official news agency said.
   The government has opened a number of long-closed records to
historians in the past year.
   ``Specialists'' may now view documents of the czarist secret
police, jails and courts, Tass said. It did not define
``specialists.''
   The news agency also said ``a provision has been set'' for
reviewing documents of the Soviet Union's prosecutor's office, its
Supreme Court, the Ministry of Health, the state publishing
committee, and the central council of trade unions. That seemed to
imply that some restrictions would remain.
   The White Guards opposed the Bolshevik Revolution in 1917 and
fought the Red Army in a civil war that ended in 1922 when the last
Whites were ousted from Vladivostok.
   Tass did not define the ``liquidated'' organizations covered in
the files, but dictator Josef Stalin was responsible for the deaths
of millions of his people during the 1930s. He wiped out the small
businesses of the New Economic Policy era, a class of independent
farmers called kulaks, and various groups he considered political
opponents.
   Central State Archive Director Boris Kaptelov said the changes
will broaden the base for social sciences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-PleaBargain     01-09 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Plea Bargain,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Studies Case of Harsher Sentence After Plea Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to study the
power of judges to impose harsher sentences on defendants who back
out of plea-bargain agreements.
   The justices said they will consider reinstating the life
sentence of an Alabama man convicted of burglary. Before standing
trial in 1986, James Lewis Smith had pleaded guilty to the burglary
charge and had been sentenced to 30 years in prison for it.
   Smith had been indicted in Montgomery on charges of rape,
burglary and sodomy _ all arising from the same incident. In a
plea-bargain agreement, he pleaded guilty to rape and burglary, and
the sodomy charge was dropped.
   Smith was sentenced to 30 years on each of the two counts, with
the sentences to run concurrently.
   He then sought to withdraw his guilty plea, and a state appeals
court allowed him to do so. It ruled that Smith had not been
informed that he would be sentenced as a repeat offender, and would
be subject to stiffer penalties than he expected.
   Smith stood trial, was convicted and then was sentenced by the
same state judge who had earlier accepted his plea bargain.
   The judge sentenced Smith to separate life terms for the sodomy
and burglary convictions, and to 150 years for the rape conviction.
   A state appeals court upheld the life terms for sodomy and
burglary, but set aside the sentence for Smith's rape conviction.
   The Alabama Supreme Court last June 24 threw out Smith's life
sentence on the burglary conviction, ruling that it represented
judicial vindictiveness.
   ``It is clear that the trial judge increased (Smith's) sentence
because of his subjective observations and not because of any
objective evidence of events subsequent to (Smith's) first
conviction,'' the state said.
   The June ruling did not affect Smith's life sentence for the
sodomy conviction.
   State Attorney General Don Siegelman appealed the Alabama Supreme
Court ruling, asking the nation's highest court to draw a
distinction between cases in which defendants withdraw guilty pleas
and those in which they are resentenced after successful appeals.
   The Supreme Court in 1969 limited judges' power to impose more
stringent sentences after defendants successfully appealed their
original prison terms.
   The current case is Alabama vs. Smith, 88-333.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
