<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs     01-09 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Prosecuter Says `No Mercy' in Drug Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's hard-line prosecutor general said Monday
more drug traffickers will be executed in a nationwide
anti-narcotics campaign, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
   More than 1,000 people have been arrested and scores have been
killed in gunfights during recent weeks of the crackdown.
   ``We have no fear of increasing statistics on executions because
those who become the victims of death traders are far greater in
number than the smugglers,'' IRNA quoted Prosecutor General Mohammad
Mousavi Khoeniha as saying.
   He was addressing a Tehran seminar on enforcing new laws that
take effect Jan. 21. They impose a mandatory death sentence on
anyone caught carrying an ounce or more heroin, morphine, codeine or
methadone, or smuggling more than 11 pounds of any narcotic.
   Iran's official media reported 19 convicted drug traffickers were
executed Friday and Saturday in Tehran and other cities.
   Khoeniha emerged as a hardliner in the 1979 revolution. He
advocated mass execution of opposition members and was mentor of
militants who seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in November 1979 and
held 52 Americans hostage for 444 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
