<FIRST>u i PM-ChemicalConference 5thLd-Writethru a0646 01-09 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Conference, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0646,0790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Accuses U.S. Of Hypocrisy, Helping Israel Build Weapons Stockpiles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with comments from Libyan foreign minister.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya's foreign minister said today the United
States has launched ``vile campaigns'' against Libya while helping
Israel build a stockpile of nuclear, chemical and biological weapons.
   Foreign Minister Jadallah Azouz Ettalhi also said U.S.
allegations Libya has a plant intended to build chemical weapons are
``clearly false.''
   Earlier, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze said
evidence shown him by Secretary of State George Shultz did not prove
the U.S. allegations.
   Addressing an international conference on chemical weapons,
Ettalhi said the U.S. position on chemical weapons is discriminatory.
   ``How can any member of the international community proclaim a
right it denies others, and how can it stand in the way of
international efforts at eradicating these weapons while, at the
same time, launching vile campaigns of calumny on the basis of a
discriminatory, racist position, basing itself on accusations which
are clearly false,'' he said.
   The Libyan minister claimed Israel has nuclear, chemical and
biological weapons stockpiles and that the United States provides
financing and technical assistance.
   ``This power (the United States) doesn't hesitate to aggress the
victim. This situation is dangerous,'' Ettalhi said. ``Agreed
international rules must be applied to all parties without
discrimination.''
   The five-day conference, which began Saturday, was called to
bolster flagging talks on a chemical weapons ban.
   The United States and the Soviet Union are the only two countries
to admit possessing chemical weapons. According to U.S. estimates,
about 20 countries possess or have the ability to manufacture
chemical weapons.
   The only existing document on chemical weapons, the 1925 Geneva
Protocol, bans only their use, and without enforcement power, is
regarded as inadequate by many nations.
   Vice Premier Tariq Aziz of Iraq led a move Sunday against a ban
on chemical arms unless nuclear weapons are also banned. He said
Israel has ``nuclear weapons as well as chemical weapons and
missiles that can reach many Arab cities.''
   Israel called the Iraqi statement ``blatant hypocrisy.'' Iraq is
known to have used chemical weapons in its 8-year war with Iran.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens of Israel today accused Iraq, Libya
and Syria of having chemical arms, telling conference delegates that
these weapons have been used ``by countries that made no attempt to
hide or disguise their hostility to Israel.''
   Shultz met Shevardnadze on Sunday and said he had won a promise
from the Soviets to conduct their own inquiry into the plant at
Rabta, south of Tripoli. He said at the time he believed the Soviets
ultimately would back the U.S.
   Libya has denied its plant can make chemical weapons, claiming it
is intended to produce pharmaceuticals.
   ``The American secretary of state showed me the building plan,
but that proves nothing,'' Shevardnadze told reporters today just
before leaving Paris for Moscow.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
Shultz had given Shevardnadze limited information only to show the
information was ``detailed and serious.''
   ``In response, the foreign minister indicated the Soviets took
these issues seriously and would be looking into it and asking
questions,'' Redman said. ``That's what's important.''
   Shevardnadze told reporters he had told Shultz that ``the most
important thing is to stabilize the situation after the air
incident'' during which American fighters shot down two Libyan
warlanes over the Mediterranean last week.
   On Sunday, the Soviet Union announced it would start destroying
chemical arms stockpiles. U.S. officials said the Soviets were
merely playing ``catch-up'' because the United States has been
routinely destroying stockpiles of aging chemical arms since the
early 1980s.
   Shevardnadze said the Soviet Union will not wait for disarmament
negotiators in Geneva to reach an accord banning use, production and
stockpiling of chemical arms. He said a new Soviet facility to
destroy chemical weapons will go into operation this year.
   The envoy said his country has stopped production of chemical
weapons, an announcement first made in April 1987.
   Lynn Hansen, director ofthe bureau of multilateral affairs at the
U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament Agency, said the Soviet position
``now corresponds to our own position. ... We simply don't get the
press, because for us it's more routine.
   ``When they do it, all of a sudden it's news,'' Hansen told
reporters.
   The United States halted production of chemical weapons in 1969
but resumed 18 years later to counter the Soviet build-up. The
Soviet Union says it has 50,000 tons of chemical arms stockpiled,
while the United States has about 30,000 tons. Both figures are
thought to be largely underestimated.
</TEXT>
