<FIRST>r w AM-Budget-Census     01-09 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Census,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Census Slated For Whopping Decennial Budget Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While most federal agencies are struggling with
funding cuts or small raises, the Census Bureau would get nearly
triple its current amount under President Reagan's 1990 budget.
   But don't get too excited, it's only temporary.
   Reagan proposed Census Bureau spending of $1.47 billion for
fiscal 1990, up from about $250 million in 1988 and about $559
million in the current year.
   The reason is the ``decennial'' census.
   The Constitution requires the bureau to count all residents of
the United States every 10 years. The next count will be conducted
April 1, 1990.
   That requires opening dozens of offices across the country,
mailing out more than 100 million census forms, sending an army of
people to the thousands of homes where folks fail to respond, and
compiling the tidal wave of data to be collected.
   Overall, the 1990 national head count is expected to cost $2.6
billion, but not all in one year. The costs are spread over several
years because of the lengthy preparation of forms and maps and
offices and computers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People     01-09 0940</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0977</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jan. 23 broadcast is planned of the
inductions of newsman David Brinkley and comedians George Burns and
Red Skelton into the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences' Hall
of Fame.
   Producer David Wolper was also among the eight people honored,
four of them posthumously. They were comedian Jack Benny, Burns'
wife and partner, Gracie Allen, talk show host David Susskind and
newsman Chet Huntley.
   Burns, Skelton, Brinkley and Wolper attended ceremonies Sunday
night along with 700 other people, including comedian Bob Hope,
humorist Art Buchwald, and ``Tonight Show'' host Johnny Carson. The
ceremony was taped by Fox Broadcasting Co.
   Past inductees include Steve Allen, Lucille Ball, Milton Berle,
Carol Burnett, Carson, Walter Cronkite, Jackie Gleason and Hope.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stormie Jones, the world's first recipient of a
simultaneous heart and liver transplant, was in good condition after
she returned to Pittsburgh to determine if her liver is working
properly.
   Stormie, 11, of White Settlement, Texas, was accompanied by her
mother, Lois Purcell, officials of Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh
said Monday.
   Blood tests in Texas found elevated levels of body toxins the
liver should be removing, said hospital spokeswoman Lynn McMahon.
   Doctors performed Stormie's pioneering transplant operation at
Children's Hospital in February 1984 because she suffered from
hyper-cholesterolemia, which causes great amounts of fat to
accumulate in the blood.
   She returned last October for bile duct reconstruction and was
discharged in early December. Miss McMahon said it was not
immediately clear whether her new symptoms are related to the bile
duct problem.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roseanne Barr, 214 pounds packed on a 5-foot-4
frame of outrageousness, says she sometimes thinks women can do more
in life if they are larger than life.
   ``Women should try to increase their size rather than decrease
it, because I believe the bigger we are, the more space we'll take
up and the more we'll have to be reckoned with,'' Barr said in the
February issue of Redbook.
   ``I think every woman should be fat like me.''
   Well, maybe not, says the star of the ABC sitcom ``Roseanne.''
Barr admits she'd like to lose 40 pounds, but insists dieting has
made her gain weight in the past.
   ``It's because of that horrible deprivation thing you go
through,'' she says. ``That's what made me fat.''
   But, she said, ``I swear to God that I don't want to be thin. ...
I think the sexiest thing a woman could do is to be as fat as me, or
fatter.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop Francis Schulte, who becomes archbishop
of the New Orleans Catholic Archdiocese on Feb. 14, celebrated Mass
and got his first taste of New Orleans culture _ a slice of king
cake, the Carnival season sweet. Schulte's first New Orleans Mass on
Sunday was the 174th Mass to Our Lady of Prompt Succor in
thanksgiving for what many believe was her intercession on behalf of
U.S. troops fighting the British in the 1815 Battle of New Orleans.
   Schulte, a bishop in West Virginia, was on a three-day visit
before replacing Philip Hannan, who is retiring.
   Schulte said leaving ``cold and snowy West Virginia to arrive in
the rich warmth of New Orleans'' was ``a symbol of the warm
reception I've received.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Carol Burnett says she may marry again
some day, but she'll never live with another man.
   ``If I did marry, my husband would have to live next door or
across the street because I could never live with someone again. I
enjoy my place too much to want to give it up,'' she said in the
February issue of Redbook magazine.
   Miss Burnett said she had ``worked long and hard to get my own
place ... this room I have in life. And that's very important to me
because I had been very conditioned to think I could never be my own
person.''
   But would a sex life with a mate who lived across the street be
complicated? ``No, not really. It's sort of exciting, thinking that
I'd have to sneak out for `it.'''
   Miss Burnett was married twice _ to Don Saroyan, from 1955 to
1962, and to Joe Hamilton, from 1963 to 1982.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music star Barbara Mandrell
will kick off the 1989 Riverbend Festival with a concert at Ross's
Landing on the Tennessee River.
   Mandrell, a Grammy Award winner, is best known for ``Married, But
Not to Each Other'' and ``I Was Country When Country Wasn't Cool.''
   The 8-year-old festival, which features such diverse events as
youth soccer tournaments and Formula I powerboat races, runs June 16
through June 25. Other concert performers have yet to be announced.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Designing Women'' co-star Delta Burke says
she was terrified of men and for a time hated them until she met
fiance Gerald McRaney of ``Simon and Simon.''
   Miss Burke says in the Jan. 14 edition of TV Guide magazine that
she participated in beauty pageants in real life, as well as in her
television role, and that's where her dislike of men began.
   She said until now she has claimed to be too career-minded and
too independent to think much about dating. But the truth is that
she was attacked and nearly raped several times as a teen-age beauty
contestant, she said.
   ``I started getting terrified that any man coming toward me was
going to attack me,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Nixon-TV     01-09 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nixon-TV,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nixon to Bush: Learn To Use TV</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush could use a
``Department of Television Strategy'' on his transition team, former
President Richard Nixon said in a magazine article released Monday.
   ``Ronald Reagan used TV so skillfully that he made it look
effortless,'' Nixon wrote in the Jan. 14 issue of TV Guide. ``It
would be a mistake for any other president to assume he will do as
well. Reagan was born to the breed, a performer long before he
became a politician.''
   Nixon, whose own career included such effective television
performances as the ``Checkers speech,'' and such disasters as the
1960 Kennedy-Nixon debate, lamented that the Bush transition team
didn't include a television division.
   ``Of all the institutions arrayed with and against a president,
none controls his fate more than television,'' he wrote. ``Unless a
president learns how to harness its power, his administration is in
trouble from the very beginning.''
   Newspapers are important, Nixon wrote, ``but only if their work
is picked up and amplified by TV.''
   ``A newspaper story that turns a few hundred thousand heads in
the morning can turn 40-plus million that evening if the networks
use it. Otherwise, it is usually gone with the wind,'' he wrote.
   ``Most TV reporters, like most politicians, are conscientious,
intelligent and hard-working. The majority are liberal. But because
of the media's loss of credibility in recent years, they are
sensitive about appearing biased,'' Nixon wrote.
   ``This makes them fair-weather friends. Except during the 1981
recession and the Iran-Contra affair, President Reagan got generally
favorable coverage on TV not because the reporters liked him but
because the people did.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People-Busey     01-09 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Busey,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gary Busey Leaves Hospital for Private Rehabilitation Facility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Gary Busey has left the hospital and
moved to a private rehabilitation facility to continue his recovery
from head injuries suffered in a near-fatal motorcycle crash last
month.
   The actor's family has him ``in an undisclosed facility to
continue his rehab work,'' Ron Wise, a Cedars-Sinai Medical Center
spokesman, said Monday. ``They want privacy.''
   Busey was in fair condition and ``seemed to be doing well,'' when
he left Friday, Wise said.
   Wise said the prognosis for a full recovery still holds up.
   All inquiries were referred to Busey publicist Paul Bloch, who
didn't immediately return calls Monday.
   Busey, 44, an active opponent of mandatory helmet laws, wasn't
wearing a helmet Dec. 4 when he lost control of his motorcycle in
Culver City, fell and hit the back of his head on a curb. He
underwent 90 minutes of neurosurgery.
   Busey, whose movie credits include ``Big Wednesday,'' ``Carney''
and ``Lethal Weapon,'' was nominated for an Academy Award for the
title role in ``The Buddy Holly Story.'' Most recently, he portrayed
a journalist in the HBO miniseries ``A Dangerous Life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 2348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--CocaineScouts     01-09 0101</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Cocaine Scouts,0102</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cub Scouts Find Pound of Cocaine During Hike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Cub Scouts hiking in the Upper
Newport Bay Ecological Reserve found and turned in a suitcase
containing more than a pound of cocaine, police said.
   Ben Courtney, 9, and Casey Luchesi, 8, discovered the brown
suitcase hidden in bushes during a hike Saturday, said police
spokesman Rick Bradley.
   The boys took the suitcase to pack leader Alan W. Courtney, who
opened it to find 570 grams of cocaine. The pack of eight boys and
their leader took the suitcase and narcotics to police.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
