<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Quake     01-09 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Quake,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kremlin Criticizes Bureaucrats in Wake of Earthquake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin's earthquake relief commission sharply
criticized two Armenian ministries Monday for failing to provide
plans for schooling, jobs and shelter to tens of thousands of
survivors.
   The Politburo commission said most government agencies have
finished detailed proposals for restoring normal life in the section
of northwest Armenia devastated by the Dec. 7 quake, Tass reported.
The earthquake killed 24,888 people and left 500,000 homeless.
   But the Armenian ministry of light industry was censured because
it did not produce ``specific proposals for the employment of 40,000
people and for improvement in their living conditions,'' the
official news agency said.
   About 80,000 children remain in the disaster area, but the
Armenian ministry of public education ``has taken practically no
serious steps to organize their upbringing and instruction,'' Tass
said.
   The Soviet ministry of railways, however, was praised for
developing plans to double the freight hauled on Armenia's two main
lines to 40 million tons a year, the report said. Transport
officials earlier came under strong criticism as thousands of
railcars packed with relief supplies piled up at stations and on
side tracks for lack of sufficient labor to unload them.
   The first priority goals of reconstruction of housing complexes,
industry, agricultural facilities and city and town buildings are
proceeding and should be finalized within two weeks, Tass said.
Authorities have pledged to rebuild within two years.
   The first foundation stone for a new apartment house was laid
Saturday in Leninakan, where more than 200 buildings were destroyed.
</TEXT>
