<FIRST>r w AM-Budget-Reagan     01-09 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Reagan,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Defends Spending Blueprint</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Monday that his proposed
$1.15 trillion spending blueprint for fiscal 1990 puts America ``on
track to a balanced budget'' and eventually ``a modest surplus.''
   Appearing before a group of business leaders, Reagan defended his
budget proposal, which calls for deficit spending of $92.5 billion,
as ``an excellent document that fulfills the original objectives''
of meeting basic needs without tax rate hikes.
   ``We even do this without touching Social Security, weakening our
national defense or reducing benefits to the needy ... and we do
this without raising taxes,'' said Reagan.
   The president, who underwent weekend surgery on his left ring
finger, appeared with his hand heavily bandaged.
   Reagan said that ``thanks to our record (economic) expansion, the
revenue is literally rolling in.''
   ``Raising taxes would be the surest way of killing the economic
goose that lays the golden egg,'' the president told some 150 men
and women gathered in an auditorium of the Old Executive Office
Building next to the White House.
   Reagan and White House chief of staff Kenneth M. Duberstein told
the group they would not be surprised to see opposition in Congress
to some of the administration's proposals for eliminating various
federal programs.
   ``There are some people on Capitol Hill who are already saying,
`Dead on arrival,''' Duberstein said, ``but those people simply
don't like hearing the message that this last budget of Ronald
Reagan proclaims.''
   Of his critics, Reagan said, ``Basically, what they really want
is to repudiate the last eight years and repeal the last election,''
in which Vice President George Bush defeated Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis.
   Reagan again denounced what he said was an ``iron triangle'' of
congressional Democrats, special interest groups and the news media,
which he predicted would be ready with ``a fiscal sob story'' aimed
at undermining support for Reagan's budget.
   He said that critics will say that ``revenue is scare here in
Washington, and there isn't enough money to go around,'' and told
his listeners that would be a ``flim flam story.''
   Reagan said that his final budget proposal ``places America on
track to a balanced budget, and even a modest surplus, by 1993.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
