<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--RefineryFire     01-09 0117</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Refinery Fire,0119</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Put Out in Refinery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IZMIR, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out at a refinery near this
Aegean coastal city but was put out an hour later, it was reported
Monday.
   The fire at the Ali Aga refinery started in the unit that
produces bottled gas for kitchen use, according to the semi-official
Anatolia News Agency and independent Hurriyet News Agency.
   Zekeriya Oral, deputy director of the state-owned company that
runs Turkey's refineries said the fire was caused by a gas leak and
did not cause extensive damage and would not cause a halt in
production.
   Ali Aga is one of Turkey's four major oil refineries built with
Soviet aid 19 years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FirstCemetery     01-09 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-First Cemetery,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cemetery Marks Milestone For Planned Community</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Rouse Co. designed the community of
Columbia 21 years ago, no one thought about endings, just beginnings.
   Now, with a population that has grown to 70,500, the community
built on farm land halfway between Baltimore and Washington are
about to be offered a place to be buried.
   Later this month, grave sites will go on sale for Columbia's
first cemetery, a development that marks the community's coming of
age, according to Jerry Brock, vice president of senior development
at Rouse.
   ``It represents the fact that it's an established community. It's
no longer a new town or an experiment,'' Brock said.
   The Rouse Co. began thinking about a cemetery for Columbia in the
late 1970s, but only in the past few years has Columbia's population
reached a point to make a cemetery financially possible, Brock said.
   Last year, Rouse officials sold 28 acres to Harvey Geller, 58, a
semi-retired Bethesda resident with more than 30 years managing
cemeteries in Massachusetts, Virginia and Pennsylvania.
   ``This is the first time I've ever started one brand new,''
Geller said. ``It's a labor of love.''
   A stone wall at the entrance has been built, five acres of wooded
land have been cleared, and shrubs have been planted at the 28-acre
cemetery.
   The cemetery should hold about 25,000 graves, enough to supply
Columbia's needs for about 50 years, Geller said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 2348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--ArthritisDrug     01-09 0102</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Arthritis Drug,0104</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pharmaceutical Company Will Sell Drug for Arthritis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lederle Laboratories announced Monday it will
begin marketing a drug called methotrexate for treating severe
rheumatoid arthritis.
   Many specialists had started using the drug well before federal
regulators approved it for arthritis treatment last October, said
Floyd Pennington of the Arthritis Foundation in Atlanta.
   Doctors can legally prescribe a marketed drug for any use.
Methotrexate had been sold for treating cancer and severe psoriasis.
   For arthritis, the drug is to be used with patients who have not
responded adequately to other treatments, said Lederle of Wayne, N.J.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 2349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-FratSuspended     01-09 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Frat Suspended,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspended University Of Mississippi Fraternity Reinstated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sigma Alpha Epsilon has a new house on
Fraternity Row at the University of Mississippi after being
suspended last fall when one of its pledges was charged with rape.
   The fraternity was allowed to move into the house over the
weekend, Associate Dean of Students Sparky Reardon said.
   University officials said the social organization had been
suspended for exhibiting a ``chronic disregard for existing rules
and guidelines.''
   University officials said an investigation revealed the
fraternity had served alcohol at an unsanctioned party with Chi
Omega sorority at the Oxford Country Club on Sept. 23. Questions
about the party arose after a freshman pledge, Stover L. Smith III
of Metarie, La., was charged with rape in an alleged attack on a Chi
Omega pledge.
   Smith, who has since withdrawn from school, recently pleaded
innocent. No trial date was set, and he was freed on $50,000 bond.
   Reardon said the fraternity appealed to the dean of students for
reinstatement and received approval to return to campus. All
privileges were restored.
   ``Their national organization and their alumni had done a great
deal of work in rectifying the situation and we're satisfied that
they have done all we asked them to,'' Reardon said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Tri-RailCommuter     01-09 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tri-Rail Commuter,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Florida Enters Commuter Train Age</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,600 passengers climbed aboard the
green-and-white cars of the Tri-Rail commuter line Monday, eager to
take part in the first day of regular service on south Florida's new
commuter train.
   ``It's beyond our expectations,'' Broward County Commissioner Ed
Kennedy said of initial response to the train line, which runs
between West Palm Beach and Miami. ``Our objective is to hold those
who rode it and build on that.''
   Kennedy, chairman of the Tri-County Commuter Rail Organization,
said passenger totals should grow as communities improve bus
connections and traffic worsens on Interstate 95.
   The 67-mile train line was born as an answer to traffic problems
expected during almost five years of planned construction to widen
I-95 between Boca Raton and Miami.
   But officials hope it will become popular enough to survive
beyond that.
   The federal government provided 90 percent of the $118 million
needed for the trains, with the state and local governments picking
up the rest. Federal transportation officials are carefully watching
the project, the largest of several in the nation using existing
Amtrak or freight tracks to create commuter lines.
   The track record on mass transit in South Florida is not good.
Metrorail, a $1 billion elevated railway system in Dade County, has
failed to attract many riders.
   Commuter Bill Morgan said he was riding because ``the drivers in
South Florida are the worst I've ever known.''
   Adam White, a commuter who boarded in Palm Beach County, said
riding the train ``is less stressful. You can think more ... plan
the week more.''
   Kennedy said he hopes to see the daily passenger total grow to
14,000 in three years.
   He said he knew of only two problems Monday morning: a
malfunctioning switch that delayed a train 20 minutes; and a 20 mph
speed limit on a stretch of track in Dade County that needs to be
lifted.
   Longer range problems include an $800,000 station near the Fort
Lauderdale airport that may be torn down because it is directly
underneath the flight path of planes and a shortage of bus service
to many of the stations.
   No fares will be charged for riding the train until May 1, when a
one-way trip of any length will cost $2.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 2349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--ChappedLips     01-09 0109</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Chapped Lips,0111</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lip Balm For Chapped Lips Stolen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wisconsin's frigid temperatures and
gusting winds apparently persuaded one thief to seek better
protection from chapped lips _ lots of protection.
   David D. Bohler, assistant manager of a K mart store in
Janesville, reported that 48 tubes and 432 jars of a lip balm were
stolen from his car Saturday night, police said.
   Bohler told police he was transferring the merchandise to another
K mart store and had parked his car with the merchandise in his
garage overnight.
   He discovered the merchandise was missing Sunday morning. Police
say the lip balm was worth about $200.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Uganda-Convoy     01-09 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Uganda-Convoy,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Worker Killed by Gunmen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen attacked a relief convoy in Uganda on Monday
and killed one worker, then apologized on the spot and said it was a
mistake, the Red Cross said.
   Ugandan Red Cross worker Michael Egabu was shot to death,
according to the International Committee of the Red Cross.
   Juerg Buehler of Switzerland, a Red Cross delegate who was
driving the car in which Egabu was riding, was injured in the
attack, which occurred near the towns of Soroti and Amuria in
eastern Uganda, the committee said.
   Marjolaine Martin, a spokeswoman at the organization's Geneva
headquarters, said the gunmen apologized to another Red Cross
delegate in the three-vehicle convoy and said the attack was a
mistake.
   The number of gunmen involved was not given.
   The convoy, which was taking relief supplies to displaced people,
was clearly marked with the Red Cross' emblem, the committee said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
