<HEAD>Opposition Leader Demands Roh Punish Top Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Young-sam said
Monday that President Roh Tae-woo must remove and put on trial
senior officials who played key roles in the authoritarian
government of former president Chun Doo-hwan.
   Kim, leader of the Reunification Democratic Party, said South
Korea faces renewed political instability if the government fails to
expose and bring to justice all those involved in corruption and
human rights abuses under Chun.
   ``We need stability. Stability can only be realized through
liquidation of past misdeeds,'' Kim said in an interview with The
Associated Press.
   He said Roh must keep a promise to hold a referendum to give
voters the opportunity to evaluate his performance. Roh made the
promise just before the December 1987 presidential elections.
   ``This is the promise he made to the people,'' Kim said.
   Kim said the nation would not wait indefinitely for a referendum,
but he declined to set any time limits for holding the measure. He
also declined to comment on whether he thought Roh could win a
referendum.
   The government's Democratic Justice Party has said a decision
will be made in the next few months on holding a referendum.
Government officials say they are confident Roh would win a majority.
   Kim cast doubt on Roh's willingness to take necessary action to
expose and punish corruption and human rights abuses under Chun's
rule. He said top Chun aides remained in the government and ruling
party and must be expelled and put on trial.
   He also insisted that former president Chun be made to testify
before the National Assembly inquiry into misdeeds under his
government. But Kim said he opposes jailing Chun because he was once
president.
   Roh had to remove the legacy of the Chun era and proceed against
those guilty of abuses or his government would be rejected by South
Koreans, Kim said. ``The people would never accept or tolerate
anything else,'' he said.
   Chun, a former general who took power with military backing in
1980, went into rural exile in November after apologizing to the
nation for abuses under his rule.
   Chun accepted moral responsibility for his government's abuses,
but denied he was involved. A number of Chun's relatives and aides
have been convicted or charged with embezzlement and other crimes.
   Resolving the Chun legacy is the main political challenge facing
South Korea and it had to be resolved soon, Kim said. Failure to
resolve the crisis would threaten political stability, he said.
   The National Assembly resumes its investigation Tuesday into
abuses under Chun's rule. The government is attempting to block
assembly demands that Chun be made to testify before lawmakers.
   Roh, a former ally of Chun, wants to limit the furor over Chun
without damaging his government, which is identified with his
predecessor in the eyes of many Koreans.
   Roh, a former general, defeated Kim Young-sam and rival
opposition leader Kim Dae-jung in presidential elections in
December, 1987 after the two Kims split the opposition vote.
</TEXT>
