<SECOND>AM-Syria-Morocco,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syria, Morocco Agree to Resume Diplomatic Ties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria and Morocco agreed Monday to resume
diplomatic relations after a 30-month break, the two countries
announced.
   An announcement on official Damascus Radio said Syria and Morocco
had decided to act because of ``brotherly mediation'' by Saudi
Arabia to achieve Arab solidarity.
   Saudi Arabian Crown Prince Abdullah bin Abdel-Aziz left Damascus
on Saturday after two days of talks with Syrian President Hafez
Assad and flew to Rabat, Morocco's capital, for talks with Moroccan
leaders.
   ``This decision follows a fraternal initiative undertaken by
Saudi Arabia and is aimed at eliminating obstacles blocking
concentrated Arab action to face up to the dangers that menace the
Arab nation,'' said a communique issued in Rabat.
   Assad severed relations with Rabat July 27, 1986, to protest a
meeting between King Hassan and the then Israel Prime Minister,
Shimon Peres.
   Monday's move raised speculation the Syrians may be moving closer
to ending feuds with its main Arab rivals, Egypt and Iraq.
   Damascus Radio made no mention of those countries, but Abdullah
said before he left Damascus that his talks with Assad had been
aimed at bolstering Arab solidarity.
   He said he discussed Syria's rifts with Morocco, Egypt and Iraq.
   Syria, like most Arab states, severed links with Cairo over the
late President Anwar Sadat's 1979 peace treaty with Israel. An Arab
summit last year gave the green light for Arabs to restore ties with
Cairo.
   Most have done so, but hardline states such as Syria have refused
and blocked moves to readmit Egypt into the 22-member Arab League.
   Syria and Iraq, ruled by rival wings of the Baath Socialist
Party, have been feuding for nearly a decade.
   These rifts have been a major obstacle in the Arab quest for long
elusive unity to confront Israel. Saudi Arabia and Jordan have been
trying for years to reconcile Syria with its rivals.
</TEXT>
