<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     01-09 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ideologue Warns Party Unity In Danger, Rally Banned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities banned a dissident
rally Monday, and the Communisty Party's chief ideologist warned
that right-wing adventurism threatens the party's rule, as it did in
1968.
   The speech by ideologist Jan Fojtik to party ideologues in
western Pilsen town suggested division among communists about how to
proceed amid growing calls for economic and political reforms to
match changes in the Soviet Union.
   Fojtik is among orthodox leaders who have refused to countenance
political reforms or dialogue with increasingly active independent
groups.
   Prague authorities banned a rally called for Sunday by Charter 77
and four other independent groups to commemorate Jan Palach, a Czech
student who burned himself to death in January 1969 to protest the
Warsaw Pact invasion to crush Poland's communist-led reforms.
   Human rights activist Anna Sabatova said the rally will go ahead
in Wenceslas Square despite the ban, which she said was made known
Friday.
   Fojtik's speech attacked independent groups, repeating charges
they are ``manipulated'' by anti-communist centers abroad, but also
expressed doubt about changes elsewhere in the Soviet bloc.
   ``There are voices of dissonance, unusual and unexpected opinions
reflecting not only confusion and uncertainty but sometimes also
extreme positions, including casting doubts over the entire history
of socialism and its claims on the future,'' he said.
   ``Even today we don't have the right to ignore the danger
socialism is in,'' he added, warning communists not to underestimate
``forces willing to ... repeat the right-wing adventure of the late
1960s.''
   In 1968, the Soviets and their supporters charged communist rule
was threatened by Western-backed ``counterrevolution'' and used this
as justification to invade Poland.
   Palach protested the invasion and continuing presence of Soviet
troops on Jan. 16, 1969, by setting himself alight in Wenceslas
Square.
   He died three days later. Thousands of Czechoslovaks, shocked and
moved by his protest, attended his funeral.
   Meanwhile, Ms. Sabatova reported a 37-year-old Communist Party
member died Dec. 3 after he was beaten by police who accused him of
a minor traffic offense.
   In a telephone call to The Associated Press bureau in Vienna, Ms.
Sabatova said an autopsy showed Josef Babka died the following day
from internal bleeding that caused a circulatory collapse. He lived
in Mihalovce, a town in east Slovakia close to the Soviet border.
   Meanwhile, an emigre source in Vienna said the recently formed
Czechoslovak Helsinki Committee has appealed to authorities to allow
a 48-year-old Charter 77 signatory to emigrate to West Germany for
heart surgery.
   So far, authorities have refused permission to Walter Kania.He
was granted an early release from prison last May after he suffered
two heart attacks while serving a 10-year jail term.
   The new committee, which includes prominent activists such as
banned playwright Vaclav Havel, appealed to the Czechoslovak Justice
Ministry on Jan. 5, said the source.
</TEXT>
