<FIRST>r a AM-Filmmaker'sCrusade     01-09 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Filmmaker's Crusade,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friend's Death Inspires Ad Urging Motorists Not to Drive Drunk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A filmmaker whose best friend was killed by a
drunken driver turned his grief into a television advertisement that
is a labor of love for a buddy who died a senseless death and the
thousands of others like him.
   ``What we're trying to do is stop people from drinking and
driving,'' Lee Gotfried said Monday. ``We die of enough things in
the world _ disease, famine, war _ I don't think we need this one
... and I think we can do something about this one.''
   Since Christmas week, his public service announcement has been
broadcast nationwide with help from the U.S. Department of
Transportation. The ad has been nominated for a top industry award.
   Gotfriend and his friend, Michael Flax, grew up together on
Chicago's South Side.
   Flax was killed two weeks after his 29th birthday in October
1985. He was crossing the street near Soldier Field after a Bears'
football game when ``suddenly this car came out of nowhere'' and
slammed into him, said Gotfried.
   Flax, who worked for a Chicago trade exchange, died instantly.
   ``He was a good guy, and it was a shame. It's true when they say
the good die young. He was a good one,'' Gotfried, 33, said in a
telephone interview.
   ``That's where the pain is,'' he said. ``He's dead. He's gone. He
doesn't feel anything. The pain is here. And it hurts.''
   Gotfried, who owns a Chicago film production company that makes
commercials, decided to channel his pain and anger into a project
with a special, personal meaning.
   ``I think it's real love,'' said Michael's father, Manny Flax of
suburban Northbrook.
   ``He loved my son so much that he had to do this.''
   Gotfried sent his proposal to an ad council that passed it on to
the Department of Transportation.
   Federal officials sent him a letter last summer saying, ``If you
can get the spot produced, we will assist you in national
distribution,'' Gotfried recalled.
   Insurance companies, soft-drink manufacturers and other groups
turned down his requests for financing, but friends donated about
$75,000 in time, talent and cash. Gotfried pitched in $6,000.
   The ad depicts a trucker whose buddy has just been killed by a
drunken driver. Lonely and depressed, he goes to a diner they used
to frequent. Their pictures hang on a wall.
   Gotfried posed for the photograph of the trucker's friend.
Singer-guitarist Dave Mason, a friend, provided the backround music.
   ``The tag line is, `Please don't drink, then drive,''' Gotfried
said.
   The spot was recently nominated for a Clio award, the advertising
industry's equivalent of an Oscar. Winners will be announced this
spring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
