<FIRST>r a AM-DrugBustThanks     01-09 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Bust Thanks,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anderson Residents Say `Thanks' For Drug Bust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANDERSON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 people have signed a
homemade card to thank the U.S. Customs Service for seizing hundreds
of pounds of cocaine at the county airport.
   Rosanne Kinley, owner of a beauty salon in Anderson, collected
the signatures, and the card will be presented to agents Tuesday at
the Anderson County Sheriff's Department.
   ``I've been with customs almost 24 years, but I don't remember
ever having a group of citizens make a presentation like this one,''
said Bill Mason of the agency's Charleston office.
   Community involvement is something law enforcement agencies
strive for, said Mason, who is in charge for the agency in the
Carolinas and Georgia.
   ``We just want to thank them for their efforts and send a message
to drug pushers in Anderson that we don't want them in our town,''
Ms. Kinley said.
   Customs agents seized 708 pounds of cocaine Oct. 5. Agents had
tracked an airplane believed to be carrying the drugs from Colombia
to St. Augustine, Fla., where the plane made a stop, and then on to
Anderson.
   Three men were arrested when the plane landed. A fourth man,
owner of the plane, was found dead the next day in an apparent
suicide. A fifth man was arrested later.
   Three of them have pleaded guilty to conspiracy charges and are
awaiting sentencing in U.S. District Court. The fourth suspect is
awaiting trial.
</TEXT>
