<FIRST>r i AM-Walesa-Wife     01-09 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa-Wife,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Leader's Wife Gives First Post-Martial Law Interview</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of Lech Walesa has followed him
onto the pages of the Polish press for the first time since the 1981
martial-law crackdown, saying she is neither afraid nor hopeful
about the future.
   Danuta Walesa, a mother of eight who generally maintains her
privacy despite the worldwide attention focused on her husband, gave
an interview to the year's first edition of the Warsaw church weekly
Catholic Review.
   The story under the headline ``A Normal Life' follows several
interviews of Walesa that started appearing in official newspapers
after labor strikes ended in September.
   They represent the first official airing of the Solidarity
leader's views in seven years. But proposed government talks with
the opposition have stalled and Poland's economy continues to
deteriorate.
   ``Realistically speaking, because dreaming is no good, I don't
see a way out of this situation,'' said Mrs. Walesa, 39. ``I am
looking at what is going on now, what is being said and done _ this
is nothing. It is terrible.''
   Mrs. Walesa said she sees the government involved in a
``psychological struggle to mentally destroy people.''
   But she said, ``People don't let themselves be tread on. Not in
these times.''
   Mrs. Walesa went to Oslo in 1983 to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
for her husband, who feared he would not be allowed to return to
Poland if he left.
   She called the trip ``a beautiful challenge'' and described other
``nice experiences, even lofty'' as the wife of the leader of the
Polish opposition.
   But she recalled with bitterness the imposition of martial law in
December 1981, when Walesa began 11 months of internment and his
union was outlawed.
   ``My martial law started in March (1982),'' said Mrs. Walesa,
when her daughter, Maria, was to have been baptized. She said she
sought permission for her husband to attend but an official told her
the day before that her petition had been rejected.
   ``I got so mad then, I started screaming at him ... At (Soviet
leader Leonid) Brezhnev, at everybody who came into my mind,'' she
said.
   Mrs. Walesa, whose children range in age from 3 to 18, said it is
difficult to raise youngsters now, when the family and the school
represent two different worlds. ``At home one thing is said, at
school another,'' she said.
   She said her Roman Catholic faith gives her strength and she does
not fear a repeat of martial law, which was lifted in 1983.
   ``Maybe what I am saying will sound funny or even strange, but I
am not afraid of anything,'' she said.
   Accompanying the article was a photograph of the 10-member Walesa
family, the first to appear in the government-sanctioned press.
   Walesa said from the family's Gdansk home that he was pleased
with the article but agreed jokingly that he was fearful of
competition from his wife.
   He said she gave the interview because ``she expected people
would like to read it and whatever she has to say, people would like
to hear.''
</TEXT>
