<FIRST>r w AM-US-Libya     01-09 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Libya,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Says Talks With Gadhafi Over Plant Not In Picture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's spokesman said Monday the
administration has no interest in negotiating with Libya's Moammar
Gadhafi over a plant the United States says will be used to produce
chemical weapons.
   Asked to comment on Gadhafi's offer to discuss the disputed
facility directly with U.S. government officials, presidential
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said, ``We don't have a problem with
communications with Gadhafi.''
   Rather, Fitzwater told reporters, ``We have a problem with his
actions. ... So we feel there is no need for direct discussions.''
   The United States contends that a plant in the city of Rabta,
about 60 miles southwest of the Libyan capital of Tripoli, is a
factory for producing poison gas. Libyan officials say it is a
pharmaceutical plant.
   Gadhafi has offered the United States a one-time inspection of
the Rabta facility, but U.S. officials said such a visit would be
inadequate because the plant could quickly be modified to hide
evidence of chemical weapons production.
   Fitzwater said that U.S. interests in dealing with Libya are
represented by third-party intermediary governments, including
Belgium and the United Arab Emirates.
   ``We certainly know their position and they know ours,'' the
spokesman said. ``So there shouldn't be any need for direct
discussions. What there is a need for is for them to destroy that
plant.''
   Libya's foreign minister said Sunday that his country does not
intend to produce chemical weapons ``for the time being'' but is
seriously worried about possible U.S. military action against Libya.
   ``I don't think our know-how will enable us _ even if we decided
to do (so) _ to produce chemical weapons in the very near future,''
Foreign Minister Jadalla Azouz Ettalhi said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
