<FIRST>r w AM-Budget-Bush 1stLd-Writethru   01-09 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0687,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Cautiously Praises Reagan Budget</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 3rd graf to UPDATE with Fuller statement;
picks up 4th graf pvs, bgng: Treasury Secretary ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush bestowed cautious praise
on President Reagan's parting budget Monday, saying he ``agrees with
its intent'' while making clear he will develop his own proposals.
   ``I will continue to review it for possible amendments after I
assume the office of the presidency,'' Bush said in a succinct
written statement on the $1.15 trillion spending plan Reagan sent to
Congress for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   Bush also said he will have nothing further to say on his own
budget plans until after he takes office on Jan. 20.
   Craig Fuller, a senior Bush aide, read the vice president's
budget statement at a briefing but declined to elaborate upon it.
   He said the vice president ``has not made any final determination
about what shape (his) budget document, or framework, or
presentation'' will take. Fuller said Reagan's budget showed that
what Bush had talked about during his campaign, meeting
deficit-reduction targets without raising taxes or disturbing Social
Security ``is do-able.''
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady _ whom Bush has asked to stay
on _ told reporters that ``work is actively under way'' on Bush's
budget modifications.
   ``It is certainly possible that much of the current budget will
remain on the table, although it is too early at this stage to offer
more specific details,'' Brady said.
   Brady also said that Reagan's budget, by proposing the legally
required deficit reduction without seeking higher taxes, meets a
goal ``fully shared by President-elect Bush.''
   The vice president, in his statement, said that Reagan's farewell
budget ``is an excellent budget which demonstrates clearly that the
targets set under the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings law can be met and
indeed exceeded without raising taxes.
   ``Naturally, I support its intent,'' he added.
   The deficit law calls for a fiscal 1990 deficit of no more than
$100 billion. The new Reagan budget projects a deficit _ assuming
adoption of all its elements _ of $92.8 billion for 1990, down from
an estimated $161.5 billion deficit in the current fiscal year.
   During his campaign, Bush advocated what he called a ``flexible
freeze'' on federal spending. The concept calls for holding the
increase in overall spending at the annual rate of inflation _
currently running at about 4.4 percent.
   Any proposed additional increases would have to be offset by
corresponding decreases in other programs _ except that Social
Security benefits would not be touched.
   Bush will have to find room in the Reagan budget outline for the
increases in spending needed for the ``kinder, gentler nation''
programs he proposed in his campaign _ including expected increases
for education, child care, expansion of the government's Head Start
program and enviromental cleanup.
   And, even though Reagan's budget appears to smooth the way for
some of these modifications, in some cases the document appears at
odds with Bush's campaign statements.
   For instance, Bush has proposed an increase of Medicaid to help
cover medical expenses for poor pregnant women and their babies.
Reagan, in the new budget, has proposed over $1 billion in Medicaid
reductions.
   Reagan's budget again calls for austerity in social programs and
would eliminate 82 programs. At the same time, the plan would
protect his defense buildup by advocating a 2 percent increase in
defense spending authority above inflation.
   Congressional budget writers have said they expect defense
spending may be one of the areas Bush looks at most closely as he
seeks to find offsetting reductions to make his ``flexibile freeze''
work.
   Both he and incoming Defense Secretary John Tower have talked
publicly about the need for more defense economies, particularly in
the area of troop strength.
   Bush aides, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said the
vice president did not want to upstage the president on Monday by
reacting at length to the budget document.
   ``Naturally, he agrees with its intent. And, naturally, he'll
have his own recommendations, or put forth potential amendments,
once he takes office,'' said one senior transition official.
   ``But he won't be presenting any of those recommendations until
he's prepared to present all of them to the Congress, whatever time
that might be,'' the official added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
