<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-US     01-09 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-US,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Discloses `Debt-For-Bases' Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Japanese banks may agree to
pay part of the Philippines' $28 billion foreign debt if Manila
allows U.S. bases to remain here, the Philippine ambassador to
Washington said Monday.
   Two visiting U.S. senators, meanwhile, pledged to persuade their
colleagues to support an agreement under which the United States
would pay $962 million over the last two years of the bases' lease.
The agreement, signed by Filipino and American negotiators in
October, needs congressional approval.
   Ambassador Emmanuel Pelaez told reporters that he had received
``feelers'' on the ``debt-for-bases'' deal from Japanese and
American financiers who are ``proposing it as a straight commercial
deal.''
   He did not give further details.
   Pelaez said the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
probably would support such a deal as a way to ensure political and
economic stability in the Philippines.
   The United States has six installations in the Philippines,
including Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay naval base. The lease on
the installations expires in 1991, and President Corazon Aquino has
refused to say whether she will support an extension.
   Pelaez said that closing the bases could ``lead to political
upheavals.''
   Also on Monday, Sens. Richard Lugar. R-Ind., and Thad Cochran,
R-Miss., said they were pleased with progess in the Philippines
since 1986, when they visited the country to observe an election
that both Mrs. Aquino and former President Ferdinand Marcos claimed
they won.
   Marcos was toppled two weeks after the election in a popular
uprising that swept Mrs. Aquino to power.
   Lugar, the ranking Republican on the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, said that he and Cochran will work for passage of the
$962 million base lease agreement.
   He also said they would try to build congressional support for
$200 million in economic aid for the Philippines.
   The senators ended their four-day visit Monday by departing for
Thailand on the second stop of an Asian tour that also will include
Singapore and South Korea.
</TEXT>
