<FIRST>r a AM-MississippiReburning     01-09 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mississippi Reburning,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>District Attorney Says Prosecution Possible in 1964 Civil Rights
Slayings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The case that sparked the movie
``Mississippi Burning'' involving the 1964 slayings of three civil
rights workers could be reopened, but the district attorney does not
plan to give it special attention.
   ``There's no statute of limitations on murder, so it could be
prosecuted,'' said Neshoba County District Attorney Ken Turner.
   But Turner said he was not aware of any new evidence, and
indicated he had no special interest in prosecuting the case.
   ``I'm interested in prosecuting any murder case. I wouldn't
single this case out,'' Turner said. ``We can't prosecute on
emotion.''
   The slayings of Andrew Goodman, James Chaney and Michael
Schwerner on June 21, 1964, have received renewed attention as a
result of publicity surrounding the release of ``Mississippi
Burning,'' which uses the deaths near Philadelphia as the basis for
a fictitious story on the turbulent civil rights era.
   The three civil rights workers were killed by a Ku Klux Klan
group shortly after they arrived in Mississippi. The FBI found their
bodies buried in an earthen dam in the county 44 days after the
killings.
   Eight men were convicted on federal charges in 1967 of conspiring
to deprive the three of their civil rights. Mississippi never
brought murder charges in the case.
   ``I think it was a tragic time in Mississippi history,'' said
state Attorney General Mike Moore. ``What we should all remember is
that it's been 25 or so years. The Mississippi we have today is a
much different, brighter, much more intelligent place to live.''
   Moore said a decision to prosecute rested with Turner.
   Turner was in meetings Monday with a grand jury and had not
returned calls from The Associated Press seeking additional comment.
Neshoba County NAACP Chairman Pete Talley of Philadelphia was out of
town and not available for comment.
   W.H. Johnson of Decatur, who was district attorney from 1964-72,
said that at the time the ``state government didn't trust the
federal government, and the federal government didn't trust the
state government.'' He said he presented the slayings before a grand
jury three times without success.
   ``I felt it should be tried at the local level, but you had to
have indictments to do it,'' he said.
   Six weeks after the bodies were found, a Neshoba County grand
jury was impaneled and subpoenas were issued to FBI agents. However,
FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover told a circuit judge his agents would
not disclose any information.
   FBI agents said they didn't turn over information because they
had to protect their sources from possible violence.
   In its report, the grand jury said its investigation had been
``curtailed, and in fact stymied, by the failure and refusal of
agents'' to testify.
   The county grand jury in September 1964 defended local law
enforcement officials, saying they had done ``an exceptional job of
maintaining law and order in this county, even in the face of
drastic provocation....''
   But retired agent Joseph Sullivan, who led the FBI investigation
   into the murders, had another view of the case.
   
   ``Neshoba was an incredibly closed and racist county,'' he said
recently. ``The county's law enforcement officers knew what was
happening, the blacks and Indians in the county were almost supine,
and practically none of the whites in Philadelphia would cooperate
with us in solving the case; we found that almost every adult white
male in the county had connections with the Ku Klux Klan.''
   When the state of Mississippi failed to indict anyone in the
case, the federal government stepped in and charged 18 men with
conspiring to violate the victims' civil rights. Eventually, eight
were convicted and given sentences ranging from three to 10 years.
</TEXT>
