<FIRST>r a AM-SeditionTrial     01-09 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sedition Trial,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Heads For Trial's Opening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury was selected Monday to hear the
long-delayed trial of three avowed revolutionaries accused of
plotting to overthrow the government.
   It took 68 days in court to select jurors in a case that has
already cost more than $3 million. Both sides predict the trial will
last a year, even with the number of defendants whittled from eight
to three. Opening arguments were set for Tuesday.
   The three face charges of seditious conspiracy, or plotting to
topple the government by force; racketeering conspiracy; and
racketeering enterprise. They each face up to 60 years in prison and
$60,000 in fines if convicted.
   Up to 350 witnesses could be called to testify. Observers must
pass through two metal detectors to reach the courtroom, which an
estimated 40 marshals take turns guarding.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Loucks will present the
government's case against the defendants, whom he calls
``terrorists.''
   Loucks has alleged in court documents that the defendants are
dangerous members of an underground group that conspired to rob
banks and carry out at least 19 bombings, including an explosion
that rocked the Suffolk County Courthouse in 1976 and severed a
man's leg. The bombings injured 21 others.
   The indictment also alleges that the defendants plotted the 1981
murder of a New Jersey state trooper and two attempted murders in
Massachusetts and Maine.
   Defendant Raymond Luc Levasseur, 42, of Maine, will represent
himself, and attorneys will represent Levasseur's wife, Patricia
Gros Levasseur, 40, and Richard Williams, 41, of Boston.
   The defendants have maintained that what the prosecution
describes as terrorism is actually resistance to imperialistic
policies of the U.S. government in Central America and other places.
   Their attorneys have argued against the dangers of the seditious
conspiracy statute that makes it a crime to carry out plots to put
down or destroy the government. They maintain that the statute is
vague and so broad that it could be used to prosecute such minor
acts of civil disobedience as protests outside military
installations.
   ``What's at stake here is not just the rights of the people on
trial, it's the rights of every American,'' William Newman, who
represents Mrs. Levasseur, said Monday.
   All but five of the 17 jurors were picked at one fell swoop
Monday from a prescreened group of 45. Jury selection began in
April. Attorneys depleted the jury pool before they could pick the
alternates to sit with the panel of 12 jurors.
   After the jurors were seated, U.S. District Judge William G.
Young explained the charges and asked them to suspend judgment until
the evidence had been presented.
   ``The government has to prove somebody actually did something to
make a conspiracy come about,'' he said. ``On no account can a
person be prosecuted for his political beliefs.''
   The three defendants are all that remain of the eight who were
arrested in Ohio, Virginia and Massachusetts, most of them in 1984,
in what the prosecution has called the largest manhunt since the
Lindbergh kidnapping.
   Charges were dropped in August against two of the defendants _
Thomas W. Manning, 42, of Maine, and Jaan Karl Laaman, 40, of East
Boston _ because they were already serving long sentences.
   Manning's wife, Carol, 33, pleaded guilty this month, and Young
decided last week to hold a separate trial for Laaman's wife,
Barbara J. Curzi-Laaman, 31.
   One other defendant, Christopher King, 38, has been tried
separately and found guilty on the single count of seditious
conspiracy. He was sentenced to seven years in prison.
</TEXT>
