<HEAD>Shiite Militiamen Hacking Each Other to Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Many victims...' to CORRECT quote to include
specific villages. Pick up 7th pvs, `Amal and...' INSERT one graf after
13th graf pvs, `The battle...' UPDATING with Amal victory claim. Picks
up 14th pvs, `The roar...' with minor editing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEI1,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KFAR MELKI, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militiamen hacked
each other to death in ``horrific'' fighting Monday in which
Syrian-backed guerrillas recaptured strategic villages from
fundamentalists, police said.
   At least 80 people have been killed and 200 wounded as the
embattled villages changed hands in house-to-house combat between
the mainstream Amal militia and fundamentalist Hezbollah since
daybreak Sunday, said police.
   It was the highest 36-hour toll since the power struggle began in
April to dominate Lebanon's 1 million Shiites, the largest sect in
this nation of 4 million. Nearly 500 people have been killed and
1,500 injured in the confrontation.
   A police spokesman in Sidon, south Lebanon's provincial capital,
said fighters are committing ``horrific atrocities.'
   ``They're knifing, hacking and gunning each other to death in
Kfar Filla and Jbaa,'' he said.
   ``Many victims have been hacked to death in Kfar Melki, Kfar
Hatta and Kfar Beit. Others had their throats cut and some were
headless. Many were riddled with bullets,'' said the spokesman, who
cannot be identified under standing regulations.
   Amal and Hezbollah accused each other of ``atrocities and summary
executions.''
   Amal, Arabic for ``Hope,'' launched a counterattack before dawn
Monday and retook three of five villages seized by Hezbollah in a
lightning onslaught Sunday in south Lebanon's Iklim el-Tiffah, or
Apple Province.
   Reporters who drove into the battle area, near Israel's
self-designated ``security zone,'' said fierce fighting is raging
for the two other villages.
   The chain of hamlets lies along the main road from Sidon port, 25
miles south of Beirut, to the Israeli-held border enclave.
   Reporters said Amal drove Hezbollah out of the battered villages
of Kfar Hatta, Kfar Melki and Kfar Beit in hand-to-hand fighting.
   An Amal commander in Kfar Melki said about 1,000 of his men used
Syrian-supplied T-54 tanks to attack Kfar Filla and Jbaa, where 500
Hezbollah members are holed up.
   ``The battle for liberation will continue until the Hezbollah
cancer is uprooted from the whole of south Lebanon,'' said commander
Mohammed Ghossein.
   Amal said in a late night communique in Beirut that its fighters
recaptured Kfar Filla and were mopping up the last pockets of
resistance in Jbaa. The Sidon police spokesman said he could not
confirm this.
   The roar of multibarreled rocket launchers and tank fire boomed
across hills and valleys from Kfar Filla and Jbaa as reporters
watched from a distance.
   Cars hit by rocket-propelled grenades smoldered in the streets of
Kfar Hatta and Kfar Melki, whose 8,000 inhabitants spent the night
hiding in apple orchards and olive groves.
   ``They've burned my house, but God has burned them in Amal's
wrath!'' screamed Aisha Barhoum, a 35-year-old Shiite woman who
found her one-story house in Kfar Melki gutted.
   ``We've been liberated from Hezbolshaitan,'' she said, making a
pun with the Arabic for ``Party of Satan'' on Hezbollah's name,
which means ``Party of God.''
   Kfar Beit was almost deserted. Only two dozen of its 1,000
residents were seen; the rest apparently had fled.
   Iran and Syria, Tehran's main Arab ally in Iran's war against
Iraq, have been trying to rein in their feuding Lebanese proxies
despite differing interests in Lebanon.
   Ali Mohammed Besharati, Iran's first deputy foreign minister,
left Tehran on Monday for Syria to mediate between leaders of the
warring factions, the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   Hezbollah wants to establish an Islamic republic in Lebanon
fashioned after Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's regime.
The more secular Amal is aligned with neighboring Syria, a secular
state.
   Police said Amal and Hezbollah gunners were locked in artillery
duels around other south Lebanon villages.
   In Tyre, south of Sidon, police said Amal militiamen rounded up
150 Hezbollah partisans in overnight house raids in the city and
surrounding villages.
   Syrian troops patrolled Beirut in the residential districts of
Noweiri and Bourj Abu Haidar where Amal and Hezbollah clashed for
two hours Sunday.
   Hezbollah's Sunday offensive in the south marked a comeback by
the fundamentalists, who were driven out of the region by Amal in a
four-day battle in April.
</TEXT>
