<HEAD>23 Palestinians Reported Wounded During General Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with three more wounded, 63 arrested
after protest outside prison; Shamir saying European Community too pro-Palestinian.
Pick up 9th pvs, `Israeli settlers...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops shot and wounded 26 Palestinians during
clashes Monday, Arab reports said, as a general strike ordered by
Islamic fundamentalists and PLO-backed leaders closed down the
occupied territories.
   The worst clash erupted in the Khan Yunis refugee camp in the
occupied Gaza Strip, where Israeli soldiers opened fire on
stone-throwing youths and wounded 11, Arab reporters said.
   Ten Palestinians were admitted to Nasser Hospital near the camp,
including a 5-year-old boy with a gunshot wound in the right leg,
doctors said. A 27-year-old Palestinian involved in the clash
underwent emergency surgery at Ahli Arab Hospital in Gaza City for
removal of a bullet in the chest, the hospital said.
   Four Palestinians also were shot in the Farah refugee camp near
Nablus, including two teen-agers in critical condition with bullet
wounds to their stomachs, Palestinian doctors said.
   Army spokesmen confirmed 16 wounded, included four in Farah, two
in Khan Yunis and one in the Gaza Strip town of Rafah. The
spokesman, who cannot be identified under military rules, said he
was checking further.
   A 35-year-old Palestinian woman suspected of collaborating with
Israeli authorities was stabbed repeatedly by four masked Arabs who
broke into her home, Arab reporters and doctors said.
   They said the woman, a teacher from the West Bank village of
Hable, survived the attack and was hospitalized.
   The army said it had no report of a stabbing in Hable.
   Also Monday, 63 people were arrested after a violent protest
outside the Megiddo prison in northern Israel where many
Palestinians are detained, Israel television said.
   The clash began when seven members of an Israeli group called
``Stop the Occupation'' demonstrated outside the prison to protest
conditions of imprisonment, the report said.
   Demonstrators refused orders by troops to leave, and were removed
by force. At this point, relatives of prisoners waiting outside the
Megiddo gates started throwing stones and bottles at security forces
who fired tear gas, the report said.
   Meanwhile, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told the president of
the European Parliament, Lord Plumb, that the European Community was
siding too much with the Palestinians to play an active role in the
peace process, Israel media said.
   Shamir also gave Plumb a message for Jordan in which he urged
Israel's neighbor to become more involved in the process. Plumb is
on a two-day official visit to Israel.
   Israeli settlers blocked a main West Bank highway and stoned
Palestinian cars after a resident of the Arab village of Kafr Nakif
hurled a firebomb at an Israeli car the night before, Palestinian
news reports said.
   They said 15 Arab cars were damaged on the highway connecting
Nablus with Qalqilya. The army confirmed the firebombing, which
caused no injuries or damage, but said it had no information on the
settlers' roadblock.
   The daily Haaretz reported Monday that Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin had renewed secret contacts with Palestinians on convening
municipal elections in the occupied territories for the first time
since 1976.
   The meetings at Rabin's Tel Aviv office were held in secret to
protect Arab participants from attacks by Palestinian nationalists,
the newspaper said.
   In a leaflet issued Monday, the Palestine Liberation
Oranization-backed leadership of the uprising rejected Israeli moves
for elections and called for escalation of the 13-month-old
Palestinian revolt, in which at least 348 Palestinians and 15
Israelis have been killed.
   ``Our heroic people, we are convinced that your struggle will
defeat the terrorist (Prime Minister Yitzhak) Shamir, who is trying
to end the uprising by holding elections to try to find another
leadership than our representative, the PLO,'' said the leaflet.
   The leaflet also called for a general strike Monday to coincide
with a call issued earlier by the Islamic fundamentalist group,
Hamas.
   Hamas supporters warned merchants against disobeying the strike
call. Red-painted graffiti in Nablus said: ``Any merchant who opens
his shop will find it torched to the ground.''
</TEXT>
