<FIRST>u w AM-Budget-Reagan'sLegacy Bjt   01-09 0921</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Reagan's Legacy, Bjt,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative Reagan Left New Deal and Great Society Unscathed</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan, the most conservative president
since Herbert Hoover, is leaving office after eight years with the
hallmark programs of the New Deal and Great Society not only
unscathed but thriving.
   He is also leaving a national debt that has almost tripled during
his time and office. This mountain of debt will prove to be a severe
constraint on George Bush's room to maneuver.
   Persons listening to Reagan's first inaugural address can be
excused for being perplexed by these developments.
   On that January day in 1981, Reagan denounced budget deficits and
vowed to end them. He said government was not the solution to our
problems but the problem itself.
   ``You and I, as individuals, can, by borrowing live beyond our
means, but for only a limited period of time. Why, then, should we
think that collectively, as a nation, we're not bound by the same
limitation,'' Reagan asked his listeners. ``We must act today in
order to preserve tomorrow. And let there be no misunderstanding: We
are going to begin to act, beginning today.''
   Now, eight years later, he is leaving office after running up the
largest budget deficits in history and with a balanced budget still
a distant goal on the horizon. The final budget projects a 1990
deficit of $92.5 billion and a balanced budget by 1993.
   Counting Monday's document, Reagan sent nine budgets to Congress,
none of them with balanced spending and revenues. Each spending plan
projected that the budget would one day be balanced, but only in the
distant fugure, not in the budget year under consideration.
   For example, Reagan's first budget, sent up in February 1981,
forecast a balanced budget by 1984, the last year of his first term.
Instead, the government suffered a deficit of $185.3 billion in
1984, an imbalance that was surpassed in both 1985 and 1986, a year
when the deficit hit a record $221 billion.
   In his final budget message to Congress, Reagan placed the blame
for the tide of red ink on the steep 1981-82 recession, which
lowered government revenues, and on Congress, which refused to go
along with his proposed spending cuts.
   But in the area of spending, Reagan himself decided that it would
be politically unwise to launch an assault against the major
middle-class government benefit programs.
   He put Social Security, the most enduring legacy of Franklin
Roosevelt's New Deal and the government's biggest benefit program,
off limits to budget cuts.
   As a result, Reagan's final budget projected Social Security
payments to nearly 40 million Social Security beneficiaries would
total $241 billion in 1990, one-fifth of the total $1.15 trillion
budget and a 6 percent increase over the current year, a bigger
increase than Reagan awarded the Pentagon.
   Even after removing the effects of inflation, Social Security
spending has grown by 27 percent from 1980 to 1988.
   Medicare and Medicaid, the two biggest programs from Lyndon
Johnson's Great Society, are also doing well.
   Medicare, which provides health coverage for Social Security
recipients, has nearly doubled during the Reagan years, as the cost
of health care and the elderly population have both grown at rapid
clips.
   Medicaid, which provides health care for the poor, has shot up 50
percent between 1980 and 1988.
   Reagan, struggling to contain health costs, did propose trimming
the projected growth in both programs in 1990, but even with the
cuts the government's health bill will still represent its
fastest-growing sector.
   While Reagan did trim some poverty programs, including subsidized
housing and low-income energy assistance, the budget document shows
overall spending in these areas remained relatively stable,
representing 1.7 percent of the country's total economy in 1980 and
1.6 percent in 1988.
   One area that showed a huge increase, however, was the money
spent to finance the national debt. The administration said the
government will spend $170.1 billion on interest payments in 1990.
   That means that 15 cents out of every dollar of government
spending will go to pay the interest on the $2.6 trillion national
debt, a debt burden which has almost tripled during the Reagan years.
   Interest payments surged from 2 percent of the total economy in
1980 to 3.2 percent in 1988. This development has crowded out
spending for other programs and will constrain Bush as he struggles
to find the money to fulfill his campaign promises to boost spending
for education, child care, housing for the homeless and cleaning up
the environment.
   The $170.1 billion interest payment projected in the budget for
1990 is more than the combined budgets of the departments of
Agriculture, Commerce, Education, Energy, Interior, Justice, Labor,
State and Transportation.
   ``This last (Reagan) budget is a sad testament to eight years of
borrowing from our children,'' said Jeff Faux, president of the
Economic Policy Institute, a labor-backed think-tank.
   But Richard Rahn, a leading supply-sider and chief economist for
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, said that history will judge the
Reagan years more kindly.
   ``I would have liked to see more reductions in the growth of
spending and more progress against the deficit, but as the president
leaves office, it is clear that he had enormous success,'' Rahn
said. ``By the late 1970s, people felt that the government had
gotten out of control and that taxes, spending and regulation were
growing far too rapidly.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Martin Crutsinger, AP's chief economic writer in
Washington, has covered economic issues for 5 years.
</TEXT>
