<FIRST>u i AM-Libya-UN     01-09 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-UN,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-U.S. Rhetoric Cools In Libya Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The anti-American rhetoric ebbed Monday as
diplomats worked to fashion a Security Council resolution critical
of the U.S. downing of two Libyan MiGs but mild enough to survive
U.S. and British veto threats.
   Britain agrees with Washington's explanation that the Libyan
MiG-23s acted in a threatening manner on Wednesday in flying toward
two U.S. F-14s on patrol over international waters in the
Mediterranean.
   The U.N. Charter permits use of force in self-defense.
   Libya says the MiGs were on reconnaissance and unarmed. In
Security Council debate Friday, U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters
showed photographs of one MiG with what he said were missiles under
its wings. Libyam envoy Ali Sunni Muntasser said the pictures were
retouched.
   Diplomats said on condition of anonymity that they expect America
and Britain will jointly veto any resolution critical of the United
States. The council reconvenes Tuesday afternoon and a vote is
expected later in the day.
   The diplomats said the non-aligned nations were tinkering with
the language of a critical resolution, dropping ``condemn'' and
substituting ``strongly deplore,'' and referring to a U.S.
``attack'' and not an ``unprovoked attack.''
   Council speeches Monday were more temperate than Friday's heated
exchanges between Libya and the United States and some of the other
speeches.
   The speakers on Monday _ Finland, Ethiopia, Senegal, Sudan,
India, Morocco, Bangladesh and France _ contrasted the air fight
over the Mediterranean in the first week of the new year with the
atmosphere of detente and cooperation that prevailed in 1988.
   The aerial battle and the war of words between Libya and America
``were like thunder in a calm sky,'' said Senegal's Saidou Nourou Ba.
   ``We hope every one will exercise restraint and refrain from any
act which could enhance tensions,'' said French envoy Pierre
Brochand.
   A draft resolution circulated by the non-aligned nations asks the
U.S. Navy to withdraw from international waters in the Mediterranean.
   Libyan Ambassador Ali A. Treiki told reporters later the
non-aligned nations were still discussing changes in the draft.
   ``The tone was quite different today in the chamber,'' Walters
said afterward. ``Today there was considerably more temperate
language.''
   But he said the latest compromise resolution still was ``not
sufficiently good for me to change my position on it'' _ meaning
veto it.
   Each of the five permanent council members _ the United States,
the Soviet Union, China, Britain and France _ has veto power to kill
any resolution.
   British Ambassador Sir Crispin Tickell told reporters, ``The
United States acted within its rights ... (of) self-defense, so
although we, like everybody else, regret the incident, we're not in
the business of condemning or deploring actions by the United States
in this regard.''
   Commenting on the more moderate speeches Monday, Tickell said
that ``perhaps, even in some quarters, good sense gradually creeps
in like a tide.''
   China and the Soviet Union were expected to vote in favor of any
resolution. France was likely to abstain.
   The 10 non-permanent council members are Canada, Finland,
Ethiopia, Colombia, Malaysia, Algeria, Brazil, Nepal, Senegal and
Yugoslavia.
   Canada was considered likely to abstain; the rest favored a
critical resolution.
</TEXT>
