<HEAD>$3 Billion Sought for Atomic Complex Cleanup, New Reactors</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs grafs 2-4 with new grafs 2-7 to update with Glenn comments,
picks up 5th graf pvs: According to ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Monday proposed increasing
by half a billion dollars the down payment on modernizing and
cleaning up the nation's atomic weapons complex _ a job expected to
cost $81 billion over the next 20 years.
   In his fiscal 1990 budget for the Energy Department, which makes
the nuclear warheads for the Pentagon, Reagan asked for $3.014
billion for modernization, environmental and safety programs at the
weapons plants. That is $478 million more than is being spent this
year.
   The proposal drew immediate criticism from Sen. John Glenn,
D-Ohio, who charged the Reagan budget was not enough to prevent
further environmental contamination, let alone clean up the mess
produced over the past 45 years.
   ``It's just a token of what is needed for cleanup,'' said Glenn,
who said it will take at least $1.8 billion a year ``to even just
get started.'' He urged President-elect Bush to do more.
   Deputy Energy Secretary Joseph F. Salgado told reporters the
department was ``dealing resolutely with our safety and
environmental problems'' and has established a process ``to address
this problem in the long term.''
   The department said it plans to seek a total of $18 billion over
the next five years to build new facilities and improve the existing
weapons complex of 17 major factories and laboratories in 12 states.
   According to budget documents, 60 percent of the Energy
Department's total $15 billion in requested spending authority is
devoted to research and production of nuclear weapons and Defense
Department projects.
   Energy officials were unable to provide a comprehensive detailed
breakdown of requested outlays _ money that would actually be spent
in the fiscal year beginning next Oct. 1.
   Those outlays usually run below the requested spending authority,
which includes planned expenditure obligations on multiyear projects.
   The department is requesting spending authority of $303.5 million
for designing two new nuclear reactors to replace three 35-year-old
reactors at its Savannah River Plant, in Aiken, S.C., which have
been shut down since last April for safety reasons.
   It is not clear when the department will restart the first of the
Savannah River reactors, which produce tritium, a fast-decaying
isotope of hydrogen that is needed for modern thermonuclear weapons.
   But as a replacement for the old reactors, the department is
proposing to build a new heavy water facility at Savannah River at
an estimated cost of $3.2 billion and a new gas-cooled reactor at
Idaho Falls, Idaho, costing $3.6 billion. Both would become
operational about the turn of the century.
   To clean up individual sites in the complex, the department is
requesting an increase in spending authority from $19 million this
year to $56 million in 1990 for Savannah River, from $50 million to
$55 million for the Feed Materials Production Center in Fernald,
Ohio, and from $28 million to $54 million for the Hanford site at
Richland, Wash.
   ``There has been no decision'' on shutting down Fernald or
another plant, Rocky Flats near Denver, Salgado told reporters.
Administration sources have said that the two might close at an
unspecified future date because they are near cities and would be
expensive to modernize.
   Energy Secretary John S. Herrington had asked the White House for
an additional $360 million to be spent by Sept. 30 of this year to
clean up the nuclear weapons complex, but the request was turned
down.
   Instead, White House Chief of Staff Kenneth N. Duberstein
authorized the department to allocate $150 million in unspent funds
for the cleanup effort.
   In documents sent to Congress last July, the department estimated
that the cleanup effort could cost up to $110 billion over the next
40 years.
   A more detailed classified study, the 2010 Report, estimated that
the costs will reach $81 billion over the next two decades,
according to administration and congressional sources familiar with
the document.
   That report envisaged a substantial increase in funding over
1989-90 levels, starting sometime in the 1990s.
   Of the total cleanup costs of $110 billion, nearly half or $46
billion would be spent at Hanford, which began operating as a top
secret facility in 1944 producing fuel for the first U.S. atomic
weapons, according to the report sent to Congress.
</TEXT>
