<HEAD>Angolans Bid Farewell to Departing Cubans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FUNDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children swarmed onto a parade ground Monday
to say goodbye to the first of 3,000 Cuban soldiers scheduled to
leave by April 1 under a peace agreement for southern Africa.
   They thrust flowers into the hands of officers and soldiers as
Defense Minister Pedro Maria Tonha told the men assembled at the
training camp: ``Don't ever forget Angola, because you fought and
died here.''
   The first 450 Cubans are to depart Tuesday, in a symbolic
airlift, under terms of the agreement mediated by the United States
and signed Dec. 22 by Angola, Cuba and South Africa. The rest of the
3,000 troops are expected to return to Cuba by ship.
   Angola and Cuba have asked the United Nations to pay the
estimated $800 million cost of sending the estimated 50,000 Cubans
home from Angola.
   Their repatriation is part of a plan intended to bring peace to
southern Africa and independence to South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia, after U.N.-sponsored elections.
   Not included in the agreement are rebels fighting Angola's
Marxist government with U.S. and South African support, and the
South-West Africa People's Organization, a guerrilla group opposing
South African control of Namibia.
   Tonha decorated 13 ranking Cuban officers, including Gen. Raul
Menedez Tomassevic. Among those attending the ceremony were Gen.
Abelardo Colome Ibarra, vice minister of the Cuban armed forces, and
Gen. Pericles Ferreira Gomes of Brazil, head of the U.N. observers
who will monitor the withdrawal over 27 months.
   Cuban officials at the Funda camp 22 miles northeast of Luanda,
the capital, said the ceremony brought together the largest number
of Cuban officers ever assembled outside the Carribean island nation.
   Soldiers from Cuba arrived in July 1975, to support the
government that won control after independence from Portugal in its
battle with rebels of the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola.
   The United States has said it will continue military assistance
to UNITA until the government of President Jose Eduardo dos Santos
agrees to negotiate with the rebels.
   Brig. Gen. Rafael Moracen Limonta, who first came to Angola in
1965 as an adviser to Marxist guerrillas fighting the Portuguese,
said the departure was possible because South Africa agreed to
withdraw from southern Angola, where its forces pursued SWAPO
guerrillas, and allow independence in Namibia.
   ``The problem with UNITA is among the Angolans themselves,'' he
said, standing with other officers on the parade ground. ``We came
here because of the South Africans.''
   Angola and South Africa agreed to a cease-fire in southern Angola
on Aug. 8, and South African troops withdrew into Namibia.
   South Africa captured Namibia from Germany in World War I and
controlled it under a League of Nations mandate. The U.N. General
Assembly ended the mandate in 1966, but South Africa had refused to
leave.
   All but a token South African force is to withdraw from the
territory by Nov. 1, when Namibia is to hold its first free
legislative elections.
   Some questions remain about how 70 military and 20 civilian U.N.
observers will monitor the departure of Cuban troops from a country
14 times the size of Portugal.
   Gen. Ferreira Gomes said he would rely on the ``good word'' of
the Cubans and Angolans, but another military observer said
privately his mission is ``to count heads.''
   The observers are from Algeria, Brazil, Congo, India, Jordan,
Norway, Spain and Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
