<HEAD>Justice Department To Sue To Block Proposed Joint Ventures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department announced Monday it will
sue to block two proposed joint ventures between Westinghouse
Electric Corp. and a Swiss company.
   The ventures between Westinghouse and Asea Brown Boveri Inc. of
Zurich would involve the manufacture and sale of electric power
generation, transmission and distribution products.
   ``The proposed joint ventures pose significant threats to
competition in equipment and services necessary for this country's
production of electric power,'' said Charles F. Rule, assistant
attorney general in charge of the antitrust division.
   As a result, ``the reduction of competition in these markets
would likely mean higher electric rates for all users of electricity
and higher prices for many products manufactured using
electricity,'' Rule said.
   If the anti-competitive aspects can be resolved through a
restructuring of the joint ventures, the antitrust division still
would file a civil lawsuit, but it would be accompanied by a consent
decree incorporating the changes which settle the suit, Rule said.
   Westinghouse spokesman Jim Schmitt said that ``the negotiations
are continuing that may enable the transactions to go forward.''
   Under the joint ventures announced by Westinghouse in April 1988,
Westinghouse would hold 55 percent and ABB 45 percent in each
partnership, Schmitt said.
   ``In both cases, each partner will contribute the manufacturing
plants and engineering and marketing organizations of its involved
operations,'' he said. ``In addition, Westinghouse will receive
about $500 million from ABB for the two partnership interests.''
   A Justice Department statement said competitive concerns caused
by one of the ventures focus on power transformers used by electric
utilities to convert electricity to different voltages so that it
can be transmitted efficiently over long distances. The combined
power transformer sales of Westinghouse and ABB would exceed 50
percent of total U.S. sales, which were more than $400 million in
1988, the department said.
   The concern with the second venture focused on the manufacture
and sale of steam turbine generators and the sale of major repair
services on existing turbine generating equipment, Rule said.
   Westinghouse, ABB, and General Electric of Fairfield, Conn., are
the three leading U.S. suppliers of medium and large steam turbine
generators.
   Westinghouse and ABB are two of only four significant sellers of
major turbine generator repair and related services to U.S.
utilities, along with GE and Utility Power Corp., a subsidiary of
Siemens A.G. of West Germany, Rule said. U.S. sales of steam turbine
generators and the pertinent services are estimated at over $600
million per year.
   Schmitt would not disclose the portion of each market held by
Westinghouse.
</TEXT>
