<SECOND>AM-Crash-Family,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Woman Grieves For Relatives, But Determined To Travel Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SB1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indian woman says she is going to make
the long flight home to her native country despite a fear of flying
brought on by the loss of five members of her husband's family on
Pan Am Flight 103.
   Prachi Dixit's husband, Sunil, a graduate physics student at the
University of Notre Dame, lost an aunt and uncle, and three cousins
when the Pan Am flight en route from London to New York exploded
Dec. 21 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
   Mrs. Dixit still plans to travel next month with her 20-month-old
son to her home in Agra, the site of the Taj Mahal.
   She admits she is concerned about her safety on the
trans-Atlantic trip, but that concern is tempered by the prospect of
a family reunion and by her religious faith, she said Monday.
   ``I'm excited to see my family,'' she said.
   ``I believe in God and that whatever he does is his decision, so
I'm not really worried about getting there,'' she said.
   Still, the tragedy of Flight 103 is with her. She returned last
week from Fairborn, Ohio, and services for the members of her
husband's family.
   The uncle, Om Dikshit, a professor at Wright State University;
his wife, Shanti; their daughter Garima Rattan; and her children,
Anmol and Suruchi, boarded Flight 103 in Frankfurt, West Germany,
after apparently missing an earlier flight, said Mrs. Dixit. She
spells her name differently from her uncle's.
   ``For 20 hours, we were told by Pan Am that they were not on the
flight,'' she said.
   Two members of the family flew to Lockerbie to bring the bodies
back to Ohio, she said. Other family members already have flown the
remains to India for final services.
   The grieving family was supported by friends in Ohio who brought
meals to the home in Fairborn and attended the funeral, said Ms.
Dixit.
   ``Even people at the funeral home were in tears,'' she said.
   She returned Friday to her job as a day-care teacher at First
Presbyterian Church, and to the comfort of happy children.
   ``They are so full of life,'' she said. ``It's soothing.''
</TEXT>
