<HEAD>Legislators Irate Over Reports Tax Dollars To Go For Personal Items</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators pledged on Monday they would grill
the Treasury over office expenses after reports said Finance
Minister Shimon Peres planned to have taxpayers pay for his ironing.
   The controversy came days after Peres pushed through a $600
million economic austerity plan that raised prices for basics such
as milk and bread.
   An outcry arose over a report in the Haaretz newspaper that the
Finance Ministry planned to increase its budget by at least $350,000
to fund special privileges for Peres and his aides. Almost $90,000
was allocated to Peres' personal services, such as ironing, catering
and photographs, the paper wrote.
   Finance Ministry spokesman Avi Gil said on Monday that Peres
``didn't see the budget proposal, was not asked about it and didn't
approve it.''
   He said when Peres found out about the draft after the Haaretz
publication, ``he canceled it immediately.''
   But Yossi Sarid, a legislator for the opposition Citizens Rights
Movement, said the ministry only backed away on Monday because of
the public clamor.
   The latest proposal calls for one mobile car telephone instead of
three, and grants a senior aide a Ford Sierra instead of a Volvo,
said Sarid.
   ``The other items, such as ironing and so on, will remain in the
budget, but the expenses for the photographer will be halved from
$26,000 to $13,000,'' Sarid said, adding that items like ironing
were ``highly irregular.''
   ``They won't make or break the state economy, but when everyone's
talking about tightening the belt and austerity, it's a matter of
principle,'' he said.
   Sarid said the new budget allocation would total $34,000, less
than one-tenth of the original. Besides personal items, the initial
$350,000 figure was to cover services and overtime payments for
Peres aides, Haaretz wrote.
   Gil refused comment on Sarid's remarks.
   Guided by a Finance Ministry proposal, the Cabinet decided last
Thursday to slash the state budget by $600 million. The cuts meant
drastic price increases on subsidized foodstuffs such as milk, bread
and yogurt, and additional charges for public high school tuition
and doctors' visits.
   Political figures from right and left assailed the Finance
Ministry perquisites.
   Rafael Eitan of the ultraright Tzomet Party said Peres was
setting a bad personal example and Ran Cohen of the left-wing
Citizens Rights Movement demanded that Peres reduce his budget by 15
percent rather than raise it.
   The parliamentary Finance Committee did not discuss the
controversy during its meeting Monday, but chairman Ariel Weinstein
told The Associated Press: ``I got the feeling it will become an
important issue.''
   He said the committee would demand a detailed breakdown of the
Finance Ministry's budget, although the law does not require
ministries to submit their budgets for approval.
   A Labor Party official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
blamed the misstep on Peres' aides and said it would weaken Peres
within the party, whose younger generation has been challenging his
leadership.
</TEXT>
