<HEAD>Australians Win World Universities Debating Contest At Princeton</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Australian duo Monday ended the debate
over which college has the most persuasive students, winning
debating's most prestigious tournament for the University of Sydney
Union for the second time.
   The Sydney team triumphed over the University of Toronto and 114
other pairs of word wizards to capture the 9th Annual World
Universities Debating Championship at Princeton University.
   Two U.S. teams, from Yale University and the University of
Pennsylvania, were eliminated in the semi-final round Monday morning.
   Using a forceful debating style mixed with wit, the Sydney team
was the clear crowd favorite as debaters Warren Lee and Andrew Bell
argued that modern society reveres those who acquire wealth.
   University of Toronto team members Justin MacGregor and David
Conklin, acting as ``the government'' in the British parliamentary
style argument, had the task of proving that ``it profits a man
nothing to gain the world and lose his soul.''
   ``It was a good debate,'' a confident Lee said after the
Australian team finished its work. ``The masses were laughing and
hooting and screaming. You always like to see that.''
   Conklin admitted the subject ``was a tough one. Any value today
involving some notion of justice or injustice is difficult to get
across.''
   In the debate, Conklin argued that figures such as Jesus, Gandhi
and the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. shunned the material world for
larger social gains.
   ``Christ, in his death, was far more important than he would have
been had he compromised his values,'' Conklin said.
   The Australian team, however, argued that today's society does
not punish those who acquire wealth.
   ``Let's look at the real world,'' Lee said. ``People don't say,
`Let's all join the Peace Corps and be nice guys.'''
   MacGregor scored a few points by saying ``justice was served in
the movie `Wall Street.' Michael Douglas did go to jail in the end,
before he won his Academy Award.''
   But it wasn't enough to overcome the Australians' contention
``that the people who get the stuff are not punished, they get the
wealth, the repsect, and the happiness.''
   Earlier in the day, the Australian team defeated the team from
Yale University in the semi-finals by opposing the concept that
``the emperor has no clothes.''
   The University of Toronto advanced to the championship round by
defeating the University of Pennsylvania with a successful argument
that the sky is not falling.
   The debating championship, held at Princeton University for the
second time in the tournament's nine-year history, drew a record 232
participants from 18 nations.
   The debaters have delivered some spirited arguments during the
week-long tournament.
   For exampled, Cheryl Strauss of Cornell University last week
suggested that vegetables be the focal point of a new religion.
   ``I think we should all pray to vegetables,'' she said. ``Then we
could all look down and that would make us feel good.''
   Mark Voyce, a debater from the University of Maryland, had an
offbeat response Sunday when given the topic, ``How to Make Sports
More Violent.''
   Voyce said archery should include human targets.
   ``Who wants to shoot an arrow into a bunch of hay?'' he said.
</TEXT>
