<HEAD>Judge Wants Thornburgh Affidavit Before Dropping Key North Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 4 grafs with former congressman, Joseph Coors and head
of former CIA proprietary turning up on revised prosecution witness list
after 5th graf previous ``Justice Department,'' edits last 6 grafs to shorten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra case directed
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh on Monday to certify that national
security concerns would prevent a fair public trial of the key
charges against former White House aide Oliver L. North.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell said he would not grant
independent counsel Lawrence Walsh's motion to dismiss conspiracy
and theft charges until the attorney general made clear in an
affidavit that the decision against allowing certain classified
information to be released during any trial was made by high Reagan
administration officials.
   ``I have a question in my mind as to whether or not this is a
motion that can only be made by the attorney general,'' Gesell said
at a hearing.
   Walsh, who met with Thornburgh last Wednesday and told him he was
going to seek dismissal of the two central charges, said, ``I am
quite sure I could get an affidavit'' from the attorney general.
Gesell said he hopes to receive it by Thursday.
   Justice Department spokesman Loye Miller declined to comment on
whether the attorney general would provide an affidavit, but a
department source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he
assumed the attorney general probably will submit one.
   Meanwhile, Walsh disclosed he plans to call former U.S. Rep.
Michael Barnes, D-Md., and beer magnate Joseph Coors to testify
against North. Their names were on a revised list of prosecution
witnesses, which have been reduced in number from 87 to 40 because
of the plans to dismiss the conspiracy and theft charges. Coors and
Barnes weren't on the original list.
   Coors, after meeting with North in June 1985, provided a $65,000
donation to supply the Contras with a Maule aircraft and two months
later Barnes inquired about North's activities on behalf of the
Contras. Barnes received a response denying that the National
Security Council staff had provided fund-raising or military support
to the Contras.
   North prepared the response, according to two counts in the
indictment of the former National Security Council aide charging him
with obstruction of congress and making false statements. Barnes at
the time was chairman of the House subcommittee on western
hemisphere affairs.
   Also among the new names on the prosecution's witness list is
William Langton, president of Southern Air Transport, a former CIA
proprietary that was involved in both supplying the Contras and in
the administration's secret arms sales to Iran.
   Walsh disclosed at the hearing that he acted to dismiss the two
counts last Thursday after receiving letters in December from
Thornburgh and CIA Director William Webster discussing the problem
of disclosing classified information in the North case.
   The Dec. 22 attorney general's letter actually was written by
Assistant Attorney General Edward S.G. Dennis Jr., head of the
criminal division, and noted that heads of intelligence agencies had
identified material that ``posed a substantial threat to national
security and could not be disclosed at trial.''
   The decision represented ``the unanimous view of the intelligence
community,'' Dennis wrote. A copy of the letter was released at the
Justice Department after Gesell's hearing.
   Prosecutors asked Gesell Dec. 22 to reconsider his guidelines for
presenting classified information in prosecution exhibits. The
judge's refusal last Tuesday to take that step triggered Walsh's
trip to Thornburgh's office at the Justice Department, where the
indpendent counsel told the attorney general he would seek dismissal
of the conspiracy and theft counts.
   At the hearing, Walsh said his motion to dismiss was prompted by
the ``irresolution of the conflict'' with intelligence agencies over
releasing documents.
   Gesell said that under the Classified Information Procedures Act,
the attorney general should represent the executive branch in
detailing problems that disclosing classified information would
present.
   ``The decision of whether or not to release them seems to me to
be a high government responsibility and not a prosecutorial
responsibility,'' said Gesell.
   Gesell said the affidavit detailing the government's position
would be presented to the court under seal.
   North is still confronted with felony charges that could carry
prison terms totaling as much as 60 years if he were to be convicted
on all counts.
   These include obstructing various congressional and presidential
inquiries into the Iran-Contra affair by preparing false statements
and destroying documents.
   The head of the prosecution team, John Keker, estimated it would
take six to eight weeks to present the government's case, while
North lawyer Brendan Sullivan estimated the defense part of the case
would take two to three months.
   ``It's going to be a wonderful summer,'' Gesell said.
</TEXT>
