<HEAD>Shining Path Guerrillas Kill 17</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist guerrillas killed 12 peasants in
revenge raids on two villages and attacked a court motorcade,
slaying a judge and four other officials, police said Monday.
   The violence, the latest in the Shining Path guerrilla group's
bloody eight-year insurgency, occurred Sunday in remote areas of the
Andes Mountains.
   Near Chaluanca, a town in Apurimac state 280 miles southeast of
Lima, a column of Shining Path ambushed the motorcade with automatic
weapons and explosives, police said. They said a provincial court
judge, a government attorney and three police guards were killed.
   Police escorting the court officials to Chaluanca on state
business drove off the attackers, authorities said.
   Officials said 20 Shining Path attacked the farming settlement of
Rumichaca, 40 miles east of Ayacucho, shooting and stabbing to death
six men and one woman and torching several of the village's 50 homes.
   Hours later, the same rebel group swept through the nearby hamlet
of Huchuas and killed four men and one women in a similar raid,
authorities said.
   Police said the Mao-inspired Shining Path was retaliating because
the villages formed self-defense patrols to resist the guerrillas
and provided government troops food and information on rebel
activities.
   Ayacucho, the capital of Ayacucho state, is 225 miles southeast
of Lima.
   Rebels have killed hundreds of peasants they suspect of being
patrol members since the military organized the groups early in the
decade in villages across Ayacucho state.
   Ayacucho, Apurmiac and other states in the central and southern
Andean highlands are populated by Quechua-speaking Indians who live
in isolated hamlets.
   The region, where customs have remained unchanged for centuries,
was the birthplace and remains the focus of the Shining Path
insurgency, which has claimed 12,000 lives.
</TEXT>
