<HEAD>Heavy Snowfall In Northwest, Strong Winds Over Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The mountains of the western United States had severe winter
conditions Monday, with wind gusts of up to 115 mph in Boulder,
Colo., and temperatures dipped to 30 below zero from Minnesota to
Montana near the Canadian border.
   Rain fell along the West Coast from Washington to northern
California, with snow from the Cascades and Sierra range into
portions of the Rockies.
   A 24-hour snowfall of 17 inches was reported at Stevens Pass,
Wash., and 4 inches of snow fell in 6 hours at Stampede Pass, Wash.
   Over the eastern slopes of the central Rockies, wind gusts of 30
to 40 mph were common along the front range. A wind gust of 115 mph
was reported at the Boulder airport and a gust of 113 mph was
measured at the Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs, Colo.
   In Wyoming, winds gusted to 63 mph at Casper and to 54 mph at
Lander.
   Bitterly cold temperatures occurred Monday morning near the
Canadian border in the West. Temperatures dropped to around 30
degrees below zero at Hibbing Minn.; International Falls, Minn.;
Wolf Point, Mont.; Williston, N.D.; St. Cloud, Minn.; Grand Forks,
N.D.; and Glasgow, Mont. Also, Gunnison, Colo., had a low of 29
degrees below zero.
   Sleet and snow fell over the Tennessee Valley, the southern
Appalachians and the mid-Atlantic states. Light sleet also fell over
central and northeast Texas, northern Louisiana and northern
Mississippi.
   Richwood, W.Va., reported 6 inches of snow and portions of
eastern Tennessee, southwest Virginia and the northern mountains of
North Carolina had around an inch.
   More than a foot of snow fell in the Lowville, N.Y., area, and in
the higher elevations east of Lake Ontario. Portions of Interstate
81 were closed south of Watertown, N.Y.
   Glasgow, Mont., tied its record temperature for the date with 29
degrees below zero, and Tucson, Ariz., set a record with 25 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 21
degrees below zero at Minot, N.D., to 82 degrees at Key West Naval
Air Station in Florida and Cross City, Fla. The low in the nation
Monday morning was 31 degrees below zero at Hibbing and
International Falls, Minn., and Wolf Point, Mont.
   For Tuesday, the National Weather Service forecast rain over much
of the Southeast from southeast Virginia to the Carolinas, Georgia,
northern Florida and the central Gulf Coast states. Snow or sleet
was forecast over portions of the northern and middle Atlantic
states from southern New England to northern and western Virginia.
Scattered snow was predicted over the upper Great Lakes, rain along
much of the West Coast, with snow from the Cascade and Sierra Nevada
range across the northern and central parts of the Plateau and
Rockies to western portions of the northern Plains.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the single digits and
teens over northern Maine and from northern Michigan, northern
Wisconsin, southern Minnesota and much of the Dakotas to Montana,
with below zero highs in northern Minnesota and northern North
Dakota. Highs should reach the 50s and 60s from the south Atlantic
Coast across the central Gulf Coast region, the southern Plains and
the desert Southwest to southern and coastal sections of California.
Temperatures should be in the 70s and 80s in the Florida peninsula.
Over much of the rest of the nation highs should be in the 20s, 30s
and 40s.
</TEXT>
