<HEAD>Hotel Loses Kosher License Because Of Helicopter Sex Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Note contents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli hotel lost a kosher license because
of a New Year's party involving a couple who simulated a sexual act
inside a flying helicopter hovering outside the hotel's windows, the
manager said Monday.
   Israeli newspapers said the couple was having sex in the
chopper's open doorway, and the daily Yediot carried a photograph
Monday showing a woman and a man who appeared engaged in a sexual
act in a helicopter.
   But Doron Gilboa of the Club Hotel in the city of Tiberias said
the couple was in fact dressed and only simulated a sexual act.
   ``They were wearing transparent clothes and only hugged, kissed
and fondled each other,'' he said. ``You cannot make love in the
cold we had then, and what's more, inside a helicopter.''
   Gilboa told The Associated Press the entire hotel was rented for
a three-day private New Year party. He said an arrangement was made
with a man who offered a helicopter for a laser show.
   ``Apparently, something went wrong and the man decided to bring a
pair of performers. He acted without our approval, and we are
considering taking steps against him,'' Gilboa said.
   On Jan. 2, Gilboa said, Tiberias Chief Rabbi David Peretz told
him that the hotel's kosher license was revoked as of Jan. 8. The
Jerusalem Post on Sunday quoted Peretz as saying the hotel has
sinned and was not worthy of the certificate.
   Kosher licenses certify that food in Israeli hotels and
restaurants is prepared according to Jewish law. The licenses are
valuable to firms wishing to attract observant Israelis and Jewish
tourists.
   Gilboa said the Club Hotel, with its 308 double suites
overlooking Lake Kinneret, or the biblical Sea of Galilee, had
special ties with religious tourists.
   ``I don't see a link between kosher and that event,'' Gilboa
said. ``Our kitchen is kosher. We have many Orthodox and religious
guests.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
