<HEAD>Homeless Man Arrested in Rape, Strangulation of Pregnant Doctor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with five grafs to UPDATE with charges filed and to recast.
Picks up 5th graf, `War said...'. Subs grafs 11-12, `Chief of...' with
two grafs to UPDATE with details about how suspect allegedly lived at the
hospital. Picks up 13th graf, `Ms. Hinnant...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man was arrested Monday in the
strangulation and rape of a pregnant pathologist in her city
hospital office. The suspect sometimes lived at the hospital and
masqueraded as an employee, police said.
   Steven Smith, 23, was found by police at a shelter Monday after
three other homeless men came forward with the doctor's personal
property and said Smith had given it to them, Police Commissioner
Benjamin Ward said.
   Smith was charged with murder, robbery and rape in the death of
Dr. Kathryn Hinnant, 33, Ward said.
   The city had offered a $30,000 reward for information about the
slaying, which Mayor Edward I. Koch called ``the No. 1 case to be
solved.''
   Ms. Hinnant's body was found early Sunday by her husband and a
hospital administrator. The pathologist was five months pregnant and
the medical examiner determined that her death was due to
strangulation.
   Ward said Smith allegedly gave Ms. Hinnant's mink jacket to
another man to sell, Ward said. Police said the doctor was robbed of
a wristwatch, $50 to $75 and the coat.
   Smith told investigators that he and another man named John had
gone to the fourth floor of Bellevue Hospital and attacked Ms.
Hinnant, Ward said. However, the commissioner said, Smith put the
onus of the attack on John, including the rape.
   ``We have not even confirmed that this person lived other than in
the mind of Steven Smith,'' Ward said.
   Investigators also found bloodstained hospital garments in a
garbage container near the Wards Island men's shelter where they
found Smith, Ward said.
   Smith told police that he sometimes lived at Bellevue and had a
bed on the 22nd floor, and would wander through the hospital without
problems while wearing a stethoscope and hospital garb, Ward said.
   Chief of Detectives Robert Colangelo went to the floor, a
maintenance and machinery area, and confirmed that there was a
``lone, dirty bed,'' empty beer cans and a stethoscope, the
commissioner said.
   Ward called it ``a crime of opportunity,'' adding that Smith's
``normal behavior when he is at the hospital is to steal IDs'' and
eat at the hospital cafeteria.
   Ms. Hinnant, who had been working at the hospital on her day off
to prepare a lecture she was to deliver Monday, was remembered
fondly by colleagues.
   Hinnant came in on Saturday ``because she was always looking for
this extra mile and that extra piece of excellence she could give,''
said Dr. John Pearson, director of pathology at the hospital.
   About 50 detectives were assigned to the case, as a debate over
Bellevue security raged.
   ``Security here isn't the tightest. It seems like anyone can walk
in,'' said an intern, Dr. Jane Skorina. But she said the attack was
``an isolated incident and doesn't affect what may happen in the
future.''
   A social worker supervisor, who asked for anonymity, said that
when she once came in on a Saturday she found it ``quite
frightening. I felt quite vulnerable. There are no people around,
even the elevators are lonely.''
   Dr. Jo Ivey Boufford, president of the Health and Hospitals
Corp., said security at the 1,200-bed hospital complex would be
reviewed, but an initial check found nothing out of the ordinary at
the time of the murder.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
