<HEAD>Costa Rica Says Summit is Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 18th, `A Costa...' to UPDATE with Ortega
insisting summit not canceled. Pick up 19th pvs, `Guatemala also...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARLOS SANDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa Rica announced on Monday the
indefinite postponement of a Central American summit scheduled for
Jan. 15-16 to discuss a regional peace plan.
   ``There definitely will not be a meeting of presidents,'' Foreign
Minister Rodrigo Madrigal Nieto told a news conference in San Jose,
the capital. He said three of the five presidents involved _ the
presidents of Honduras, El Salvador and Costa Rica _ had agreed to
the suspension.
   The other two countries are Nicaragua and Guatemala.
   ``The new date will be negotiated, adjusting the agendas of the
presidents and of the foreign ministers,'' Madrigal Nieto said.
   He said the summit may take place in February. Foreign ministers
of the five governments will meet in the Nicaraguan capital of
Managua Jan. 17-18, he said.
   Nicaragua said the summit should be held as scheduled rather than
delayed as Costa Rican President Oscar Arias suggested.
   But Foreign Minister Ricardo Acevedo of El Salvador said
President Jose Napoleon Duarte believed it could be held on schedule
only if presidents of all five countries agreed.
   On Friday, Arias suggested postponing the meeting to give
President-elect George Bush time to formulate a Central American
policy. Bush takes office Jan. 20.
   Madrigal Nieto denied that postponement could jeopardize the
Central American peace plan authored by Arias and signed by the five
presidents in Guatemala City in August 1987.
   The plan, which won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for Arias, calls
for greater democracy, an end to civil wars, political amnesties and
an end to the use of one country by rebels fighting in another.
   The pln has been stalled since the presidents last met in January
1988 in Costa Rica.
   ``What we want is not to hold up Esquipulas II, but to so
organize it that it can give better results than achieved so far,''
Madrigal Nieto said.
   He was referring to the name commonly used for the peace plan,
arising from the Guatemalan town where a key, early peace meeting
was held.
   He said the original decision to hold a summit on Jan. 15-16 was
taken ``in a moment of euphoria, as if Central America didn't have
conflicts or obstacles that could intervene in achieving better
results.''
   Madrigal Nieto said committees set up to monitor compliance with
the peace plan would have been unable to overcome differences among
the governments before the original summit date.
   In Managua, President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua telephoned Arias
on Sunday to express ``his concern about the postponement,''
Ortega's press office said Monday.
   Ortega said last week that postponing the meeting ``could mean
the death'' of the Central American peace plan.
   A Costa Rican Foreign Ministry official called Ortega's statement
``out of line.''
   Ortega insisted late Monday that the summit was not postponed. He
said on state-run Nicaraguan radio that any move to delay the
meeting ``will be through a definite decision made by us, all the
Central American presidents.''
   But he added: ``In case the meeting isn't held then, it must be
held as soon as possible.''
   Ortega also said deputy foreign ministers from the five
governments would meet on Tuesday in Managua, the Nicaraguan
capital, to work out a summit agenda.
   Guatemala also has said it opposed delaying the meeting.
   Honduras has not commented. President Jose Azcona Hoyo traveled
to Washington on Monday and will meet Tuesday with President Reagan
and Bush.
   Acevedo said Jan. 29-30 or Feb. 20 were being considered as
alternate dates.
   A technical preparatory meeting should be held as scheduled on
Tuesday and a foreign ministers' meeting could be scheduled for Jan.
17-18, he said.
</TEXT>
