<HEAD>Viet Foreign Minister Meets Thai Counterpart, Predicts Accord By
September</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's foreign minister said Monday he
expects a settlement by September in Cambodia, where Vietnamese
occupying troops have been fighting Cambodian guerrillas for a
decade.
   Nguyen Co Thach said after two hours of talks with Thai Foreign
Minister Siddhi Savetsila: ``Both sides are satisfied.
   ``Both sides have agreed it (the Cambodian problem) will be
solved soon ... by September 1989 within the framework of a
political settlement,'' said Thach, who is also deputy premier.
   Asked whether peace in Cambodia was at hand, Thach told
reporters, ``Peace would be at hand during the first six months of
1989.''
   Siddhi, the highest-ranking Thai official to visit Vietnam since
1976, arrived Monday for a four-day visit. His talks with Thach were
to continue Tuesday.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 to oust the Khmer Rouge,
whose brutal four-year rule saw hundreds of thousands of Cambodians
die from executions and famine.
   The Khmer Rouge is the strongest member of a three-party
resistance coalition battling the Soviet-backed Vietnamese. China
and Thailand back the coalition, and the United States supports the
two non-communist groups in it.
   Fears of the Khmer Rouge returning to power have grown as Vietnam
announced a partial withdrawal from Cambodia. Vietnam has said it
will pull out all its troops by the end of this year.
   President Heng Samrin, president of Cambodia's Vietnam-installed
government, said last week that 50,000 Vietnamese troops are in
Cambodia, but Western intelligence officials estimate the number at
about 65,000. Guerrillas say 120,000 Vietnamese troops are in the
country.
   Armed guerrilla strength is estimated at about 47,000.
   Siddhi was also scheduled to hold talks with Vietnam's Communist
Party chief, Nguyen Van Linh, and Premier Do Muoi.
   The Thai foreign minister is paving the way for a trip to Vietnam
by Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan, who has pledged to transform
Indochina from a battlefield into a trading market.
   Last week, the Cambodian government suggested the troops could
withdraw by September if Thailand denies sanctuary to Cambodian
guerrillas and countries halt weapons supplies and other aid to the
resistance.
   Calling Siddhi's trip to Vietnam a ``good sign,'' Vietnam's
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman, Ho The Lan, told reporters the agenda
was open and that Thach was ``ready to discuss everything.''
   She listed as topics Cambodian peace talks, concerns over the
Khmer Rouge retaking power and the surge of Vietnamese ``boat
people'' refugees into Southeast Asian countries.
   The peace talks would involve Cambodia, the guerrilla groups,
Vietnam, Laos and the six-member Association of Southeast Asian
Nations. Association members are Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia,
Indonesia, the Philippines and Brunei.
   Accompanying Siddhi was a 62-member delegation that included
bankers, investors and businessmen. Its members were to hold talks
with officials of Vietnam's State Commission for Foreign Investment,
the Ministry of External Economic Relations and Vietnam's commercial
bank.
   Thailand is interested in importing oil, wood, minerals and
marine products from Vietnam and developing tourism in the country.
</TEXT>
