<HEAD>Federal Mediator Halts Talks Between Machinists, Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 3rd graf to UPDATE with union comment,
mediation board declining comment. A version moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the National Mediation Board halted
talks Monday between troubled Eastern Airlines and its largest union.
   Chairman Walter Wallace returned to Washington and couldn't be
reached immediately for comment, but an Eastern executive said
Wallace gave as his reason the failure of efforts to keep secret the
talks with the Machinists union.
   Wallace arrived Friday for the talks in Key Largo. The sessions
were aimed at ending a contract stalemate that has clouded the
future of the airline, a subsidiary of Houston-based Texas Air Corp.
   Machinists District 100 President Charles E. Bryan accused
Eastern of sabotaging the mediation by releasing statements on the
talks to employees in what he called a violation of a news blackout
on the sessions. He also alleged Eastern failed to bargain in good
faith.
   Bryan called the airline's actions ``unethical, without
principle, deceptive.'' He said the company was ``determined to
force a strike.''
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said Miami television stations
discovered the location of the talks and began covering them Friday.
Matell said the daily employee bulletins, which were obtained by
reporters, were not a violation of the news blackout.
   Bill Gill, assistant executive director of the mediation board,
said he did not know all the reasons behind Wallace's decision and
declined to comment. Harry Bickford, another federal mediator at the
talks, also declined to comment.
   Citing huge losses and high operating costs, Eastern is seeking
major wage cuts from the union. The 8,500 mechanics, baggage
handlers and other ground service workers comprise more than
one-fourth of Eastern's payroll.
   ``The end of talks is certainly a major disappointment with
serious implications about Eastern's future,'' said Joseph B.
Leonard, Eastern's executive vice president and chief operating
officer.
   ``These talks have dragged on for more than 15 months, draining
Eastern's strength with each passing day. We desperately need the
government to provide a process to resolve this dispute within 30
days,'' he said.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said Miami television stations had
discovered the location of the talks and began covering them Friday.
Matell said employee bulletins about the talks that were put out
daily by Eastern, and were obtained by reporters, weren't a
violation of the blackout on information about the talks.
   Charles E. Bryan, president of District 100 of the Machinists
union, declined comment until a news conference, scheduled later
Monday.
   Eastern has been pressing for a federal declaration of an impasse
in the negotiations, which would begin a 30-day cooling-off period.
After that, the union could strike and the company could impose its
own work conditions on the union members.
   The union has claimed that Eastern wants to provoke a strike so
it can try to break it and bust the union.
   Wallace joined mediator Harry Bickford on Friday in an effort to
get the talks moving, but sources speaking on condition of anonymity
said there was virtually no progress.
   The two sides, who last met in intense mediation in July, have
been about $200 million apart. The Machinists were seeking a $50
million raise, while Eastern was seeking $150 million in
concessions, mostly from the non-mechanics represented by the union.
   Eastern reported $233.7 million in losses for the first three
quarters of 1988. Texas Air Corp. also owns non-union Continental
Airlines.
</TEXT>
