<HEAD>Panama Marks 25th Anniversary of Anti-US Student Riots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Manuel Solis Palma on Monday
led a parade through the capital to mark the 25th anniversary of
student clashes with U.S. military personnel that left 23 dead and
hundreds injured.
   As he led thousands of marchers, including members of his
Cabinet, other government officials, armed civilian militia and
Defense Forces troops, Solis Palma told reporters the demonstration
was ``a message of warning, but not of aggression'' to the United
States.
   On Dec. 9, 1964, thousands of students protesting U.S. ownership
of the Panama Canal mobbed the former canal zone and tried to raise
Panamanian flags over U.S. installations. American troops fired into
the crowd, killing 23 Panamanians.
   Panama temporarily broke diplomatic relations with the United
States over the incident. It prompted negotiations that eventually
led to the 1977 Panama Canal Treaties, under which the United States
is to turn over control of the waterway on Dec. 31, 1999.
   Relations reached a new low last year after two federal grand
juries in the United States indicted Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
Panama's Defense Forces commander and de facto leader, on drug
trafficking and money laundering charges.
   In February, then-President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire
Noriega, who instead engineered Delvalle's ouster by the National
Assembly and replaced him with Solis Palma. The United States still
recognizes Delvalle as president
   The Reagan administration imposed diplomatic and economic
sanctions against Panama in a bid to force Noriega to resign.
Noriega denies the drug trafficking charges and alleges the United
States is attempting to abrogate the 1977 canal treaties.
   Demonstrators began their three-mile march Monday at the
Legislative Park, site of the 1964 shootings, and carried banners
that read, ``Unity and Struggle in Defense of the Nation'' and
``Until the Year 2000 with Dignity.'' Civilian militias who were
organized by the Defense Forces last March to repel a possible U.S.
invasion carried rifles, grenade launchers and submachine guns.
   Noriega did not participate in the march.
   Dozens of foreign diplomats attended a commemorative ceremony at
the University of Panama, the national university. Rector Abdiel
Adames condemned the U.S. economic sanctions and declared ``the
lessons derived from such a memorable exploit (the riots) still
apply for the Panamanian nation.''
</TEXT>
