<HEAD>Shevardnadze To Visit Iran, Tehran Radio Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze will visit Iran in the near future, Tehran Radio
reported Monday.
   The broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, said Shevardnadze confirmed
his visit in a meeting with his Iranian counterpart Ali Akbar
Velayati in Paris, the site of this week's international conference
on chemical weapons.
   ``At this time the ground has been laid for expanding relations
between Tehran and Moscow,'' the Iranian radio quoted Shevardnadze
as saying.
   Ties between the two countries have improved following Iran's
acceptance of a U.N.-mediated cease-fire in the 8-year war with
Iraq, which went into effect Aug. 20.
   The change followed nearly a decade of strain after Iran's 1979
revolution, with Iranian fundamentalist Islamic leaders viewing the
officially athiest Soviet Union with deep suspicion.
   But the Tehran daily Etelaat said in an editorial Monday that the
Soviet Union seems to be turning away from absolute atheism and
authorizing religious practice.
   The editorial, in what could be interpreted as a comparison
between the Soviet Union and the United States, known in Iran as
``the Great Satan,'' said:
   ``Godlessness undisguised is one thing and godlessness under the
guise of religion is quite another ... a hypocritical believer is
worse than a truly godless person.''
</TEXT>
