<FIRST>u i AM-Crash-Survivors 1stLd-Writethru a0644 01-09 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash-Survivors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,0940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crash Survivors Describe Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 18th graf pvs, ``Then the ... UPDATING
with later quotes saying woman survived. Picks up 19th graf, Nick Stevenson
...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOTTINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot said there was no need to be
unduly concerned, but some of the passengers only had to look out
their window at a flaming engine to know something was very wrong.
   A short time later, the British Midland Airways Boeing 737 hit
the ground in what one passenger said was a ``shuddering crash ...
like a massive motorcar accident.''
   The plane was less than 15 minutes into a London-Belfast flight
Sunday when Dr. John McCrea looked out of the window and ``saw
flames and flashes coming out of the engine.''
   Minutes later, veteran pilot Kevin Hunt told passengers to
prepare for an emergency landing at East Midlands Airport in central
England. The jet crashed short of the runway.
   McCrea and his wife, Josephine, were returning to their Belfast
home Sunday night from a trip to London.
   ``We had been on the plane for 10 or 12 minutes and they were
serving light meals,'' McCrea said Monday from his bed in Derby
Royal Infirmary, his right arm in a sling.
   ``I felt a shudder and I looked over at the left wing,'' he said,
and the cabin crew stopped the meal service.
   ``The pilot announced that we were not to be unduly concerned,
but I began to wonder what was happening,'' said McCrea, 38. Two
girls started to scream, and ``there were more more flames in the
sky.''
   ``We went on flying for a further five minutes,'' he said. ``The
plane seemed to drop. We lost height.''
   Soon, he could see lights on the highway below.
   ``We carried on two or three minutes and there were more flashes
over the left side of the plane,'' he said. ``The cabin staff were
moving up and down securing all the baggage in the lockers.''
   McCrea read the safety instructions and told his wife to brace
herself. ``I said it could be bumpy. We carried on flying. There
were more flashes and more of what I thought was turbulence.
   ``Not long afterward the captain came on the public address and
told us to prepare for an emergency landing. It seemed like only
five seconds later we were down.''
   Passenger Gareth Jones said women wept after the pilot's warning.
   As the plane started its descent, Jones said he saw sparks fly
from one engine, as he had earlier in the flight. The impact was
like a ``shuddering crash ... It was like a massive motorcar
accident ... crunch ... blackness.''
   Jones, a 38-year-old government employee who suffered bad
bruises, said he held the hand of the distraught woman next to him
during the rapid descent.
   ``The lady next to me ... was obviously very distressed. When the
first engine went she started crying and held my hand. I tried to
joke about how these things could fly on one engine and glide
down,'' he said.
   ``Then the second engine went and she gripped my hand and I said
there was no way we were not getting out of that plane together,''
Jones said. ``I knew if I showed I had any fear she would have been
worse.''
   ``When we hit the ground there was a massive crash _ like a
multiple car accident _ and because we were right next to the
emergency hatch I could see a tree outside and knew we had hit the
ground and must get out,'' Jones later was quoted as saying by The
Times of London newspaper in its Tuesday issue.
   ``I pulled the emergency exit handle and pulled out the lady next
to me. I saw we were standing on the motorway and got to my feet,
but they immediately gave way and I fell down again,'' he said.
   He gave no further details in the interview about what happened
to the woman after they left the plane.
   Nick Stevenson, who suffered a broken leg, said that when the
first engine failed, the plane started losing altitude.
   ``Then the other engine started producing strange noises ... As
we came in on the approach run it started spluttering and then just
stopped and we knew we were going to hit the deck,'' he said.
   McCrea said that when the plane crashed, ``people were moaning
and someone said `My legs hurt.' Another voice said `Please help
me.'''
   He said the man sitting next to him helped pull his wife from the
wreckage.
   ``It seemed only a minute later and someone was crashing the
windows in over the wing ... I think I was the third person off the
plane.''
   Firefighters doused the plane with foam. ``My suit was soaked and
it was slippery underfoot,'' said McCrea.
   Mrs. McCrea, 38, who suffered hip and leg injuries, said she
prayed as the plane fell.
   ``There wasn't time really to panic or worry about it,'' she
said. ``The pilot told us to prepare for a crash-landing _ that's
what we did.''
   Asked if she feared she was going to die, she replied: ``I just
said my prayers and got on with it. There was nothing else to do.''
   At nearby Leicester Royal Infirmary, Alistair McCrory, 43, of
Downpatrick, County Down, said that after his narrow escape he
telephoned his girlfriend, Pat Miles, and proposed marriage.
   ``She has said yes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
