<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Drugs     01-09 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Kingpin Wanted in United States Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed cocaine kingpin wanted in
the United States on drug trafficking charges was arrested Monday in
this border town across from El Paso, Texas, officials said.
   Federal judicial police arrested Gilberto Ontiveros Lucero and
held him in a federal jail in Juarez, said Alfonso Sanchez Gallo, a
spokesman with the Chihuahua state government.
   U.S. officials say Ontiveros is responsible for much of the
cocaine that passes into the southwest United States from Mexico.
   Rogelio Abregon Salazar, information director at the newspaper
Diario de Juarez, quoted police officials as saying Ontiveros Lucero
was to be transferred to Mexico City late Monday or Tuesday.
   A spokeswoman with the federal Attorney General's office in
Mexico City said she had no information about the arrest.
   Salazar said Ontiveros was arrested at the home of a friend in
Juarez.
   Ontiveros was arrested on drug charges in Juarez in April 1986.
In May 1988, he was released after a federal judge in Juarez
dismissed all charges against him.
   In June, the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration offered a
reward for information leading to Ontiveros' arrest.
   Four men, including the uncle of Ontiveros, were arrested in
August after delivering nearly 20 pounds of cocaine to undercover
police in El Paso.
   

</TEXT>
