<FIRST>r i AM-France-TerroristTrial     01-09 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Terrorist Trial,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Is Defiant As Terrorist Trial Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial opened Monday of four left-wing extremists
charged in the slaying of Georges Besse, president of the
state-owned Renault auto company.
   Besse was shot to death outside his Paris apartment on Nov. 17,
1986.
   Nathalie Menigon, 31, and Joelle Aubron 28, of the group Direct
Action, are charged with murder. Jean-Marc Rouillan, 33, and Georges
Cipriani, 38, are charged with complicity.
   The four, surrounded by 10 guards, appeared before a special
seven-judge panel. They refused to stand as the judges entered the
courtroom where Besse's widow and her five children sat with new
Renault chief Raymond Levy.
   They face maximum terms of life in prison if convicted.
   On Feb. 11, 1987, Direct Action claimed responsibility for the
murder in letters sent to news organizations in Paris. The letters
said the killing resulted from a ``world clash between the
international proletariat and the imperialist bourgeoisie.''
   The four were convicted last February of criminal association,
receiving 10-year sentences. Menigon also drew 12 years for the
attempted murder of two policemen in 1983.
   Defense lawyers on Monday complained the four were held in
solitary confinement in special prisons, without opportunity to meet
or discuss a common defense.
   They pleaded their clients were ``victims of an orchestrated
disinformation campaign to neutralize their political
personalities.'' The trial, they said, was ``not only about facts
but what motivated the facts.''
   Direct Action first drew attention in 1979 by bombings such
targets as Interpol, immigration and labor offices and corporate
headquarters.
   In January 1985, it announced a linkup with West Germany's Red
Army Faction to develop a communist guerilla group in Western Europe.
   Meanwhile, Elyette Bess, 57, known as the ``mother'' of Direct
Action, was arrested in Paris Monday, 48 hours after her release on
parole after serving part of a six-year sentence for association
with the accused.
   Bess was convicted July 4. She was picked up again for breaking
regulations restricting her movements.
</TEXT>
