<FIRST>r a AM-Emperor-Tutor     01-09 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emperor-Tutor,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former American Tutor Recalls Emperor's Regret</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's regret over his role in
World War II made him feel unworthy as a father, a former tutor of
his son and successor, Emperor Akihito, said Monday.
   Elizabeth Gray Vining said from her home in suburban Kennett
Square, Pa., the topic came up during one of two hourlong
conversations she had about Akihito's education with the emperor and
Empress Nagako during the four years she taught English to the
prince.
   She said Hirohito at the time saw his son only on weekends and
not necessarily every weekend.
   ``I spoke very frankly,'' said Mrs. Vining, 86, an author of 25
books. ``I said I thought that the crown prince was very devoted to
his father and that he wanted to see his father more often.''
   Hirohito ``then said that he hadn't felt worthy because he hadn't
been able to prevent the war,'' she said.
   Hirohito, 87, died of intestinal cancer Friday without ever
shedding much light on his role during World War II. Historians
generally agree he was a figurehead who was required to approve
decisions of the military leaders, until he decided the Japanese had
suffered enough and personally announced surrender in August 1945.
   Mrs. Vining said she did not know whether Hirohito spent more
time with his son after her conversation with him early in 1949.
   Mrs. Vining, who had worked with the Philadelphia-based Quaker
peace organization, the American Friends Service Committee, became
Akihito's tutor in October 1946 when the crown prince was nearly 13
and continued in that role until December 1950.
   The American Friends Service Committee nominated her for the job,
and several factors led to her selection, she said.
   ``The fact that I was a widow, that I had known sorrow, was
important to the decision,'' she said. ``And the fact that I had
traveled in Europe, and the fact that I was a Quaker and Quakers are
known to stand for peace.'' Her husband had died in an automobile
accident.
   Mrs. Vining has been back to Japan four times since her years as
Akihito's tutor. She saw Akihito and his wife, Michiko, most
recently during the couple's visit last year to the United States.
   ``I think he won't be a copy of his father,'' Mrs. Vining said.
``He'll be his own man. For one thing, he's been in England. He's
met the royal family there.''
   From that experience, he has an understanding of how a
constitutional monarchy works, she said.
</TEXT>
