<HEAD>Peace Talks Enter Second Phase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Greek Cypriot and Turkish
Cypriot communities met Monday for the second phase of
U.N.-sponsored peace talks aimed at reuniting the Mediterranean
island.
   President George Vassiliou, the Greek Cypriot leader, and Rauf
Denktash, president of the breakaway Turkish Cypriot republic in
Turkish-occupied northern Cyprus, conferred for one hour and 45
minutes.
   A brief U.N. statement gave no details, saying only that the two
agreed to meet again next Monday. The United Nations has proposed a
bizonal federation.
   The seven-week first phase of the talks ended Nov. 7 with little
substantive progress reported. It marked the first direct
negotiations between rival Cypriot leaders in 11 years.
   Cyprus has been divided since Turkey invaded in 1974 and seized
the northern third of the island after an abortive Greek-backed coup
by supporters of union with Greece.
   The 120,000-strong Turkish Cypriot minority declared a separate
state in 1983. Only Turkey recognizes it.
   Denktash demands that power be shared equally between Turkish
Cypriots and the 550,000 Greek Cypriots and rejects demands that
Greek Cypriots be allowed to return north and own property there.
   Vassiliou said at the weekend that his internationally recognized
government has proposed demilitarizing the island and that this
should allay Turkish Cypriot security concerns.
</TEXT>
