<FIRST>r a AM-LottoWinner     01-09 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lotto Winner,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nigerian Graduate Student With Financial Aid Problems Wins $26 million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nigerian graduate student who received
financial aid was identified Monday as the holder of last week's $26
million winning Lotto ticket.
   ``My American dream came true,'' Augustin B. Jombo, the second
largest winner of the Lotto, told a news conference.
   A political science student at Fordham University, Jombo, 37,
received a financial aid check of $7,500 Friday, two days after
winning the New York state lottery.
   ``I'm going to call them and say I don't need it,'' he said,
laughing, telling reporters: ``If you call Fordham, they'll tell you
I owe them.''
   He had wanted to be a professor and do research in international
relations, but said, ``I don't think I want to teach now.''
   He chuckled as he recalled how Nigerian friends told him before
he came to the United States in 1980: ``You are going to have some
experiences that are quite unique.''
   Jombo, who has applied for citizenship, said he bought $12 worth
of tickets at a grocery store moments before the 8 p.m. deadline
last Wednesday.
   Jombo has not seen his wife, Grace, and 16-year-old daughter,
Milia, since 1980 and has never seen their 7-year-old daughter,
Tina. He said he had not called them in Lagos, Nigeria, to tell them
of his win.
   ``I'm going to call them today,'' he said. ``They should come
immediately. They should be with me now. I hope to buy them the good
things in life.''
   He will receive 20 annual payments of more than $1.2 million,
minus the 30 percent federal withholding tax required of
non-resident aliens, or about $866,666. The first check is due in
two weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
