<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv10   01-09 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 10,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tues., Jan. 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Something To Worry About? ^By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Always and ever there are things to worry about
regarding the economy's future, and no forecaster seeking to remain
employed would dare not mention them.
   To them, the issuance of warnings is professional protection,
allowing a forecast to be made but escaped from if wrong. Nothing is
lost, since most warnings are considered examples of erudition and
responsibility.
   You should, know, however, that most of last year's warnings _
inflation, dollar collapse, stock market debacle, recession _ were
changed in midstream, only to be trotted out again as the New Year
began.
   This is the 1989 list, with comments by Edward Yardeni, the
Prudential_Bache Securities economist who debunked last year's
forecasting myths and stands firm and independent from the general
consensus this year.
   _The Economy Is Overdue For A Recession.
   The expansion has lasted more than six years, a long time by past
measures, suggesting that the odds can't be bucked much longer. But,
hold on; the economic world has changed, and maybe the past isn't
that accurate a criterion.
   True, there has been no general recession in that time period,
but there have been several rolling recessions. Different industries
at different times have been very hard hit, but the impact was
offset by good times in others.
   But what if these different industries slump at the same time? It
could happen, but many U.S. companies now operate globally, and bad
times in the United States could be offset by good business in
Europe.
   _Capacity Is Too Tight.
   The percentage of production capacity rose above 84 percent in
November, marking the highest level in eight years. Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan, among many, is concerned that such a level
may generate inflation.
   ``This could be a big mistake,'' says Yardeni. Why? Because ``in
an environment of intense global competition, we believe that tight
capacity stimulates expansion rather than big price increases.''
   _The Jobless Rate Is Too Low, So Wage Inflation Will Develop.
   At 5.3 percent of the civilian labor force, the rate is at a
14-year low. There is indeed a shortage of new entrants into the
labor force. The thesis appear sound.
   Still, says Yardeni, ``we believe that the employers recognize
that offering big wage hikes will only drive up their labor costs
rather than attract workers that, demographically speaking, don't
exist.''
   In his opinion, ``odds are that industries will opt to spend more
on labor-saving, productivity to substitute for scarce and expensive
workers.''
   _The Federal Deficit Is Too Large.
   Sure it is large, and that doesn't include perhaps $75 billion to
rescue the thrift industry or maybe $150 billion to clean up
radioactive pollution at the government's weapons plants.
   But there's a brighter side too. The deficit came down from an
annualized peak of $234.4 billion in the second quarter of 1986 to
$124.8 billion in the third quarter of 1988. Include state and local
surpluses and the total government deficit dropped from $174.3
billion to $68.9 billion in this period.
   The big ``problem,'' says Yardeni, is in transfer payments,
designed to redistribute income more equitably, which amounted to
23.2 percent of gross national product in fiscal 1988, a very large
fraction.
   But in terms of expenses for goods and services, the situation
wasn't all that bad. In the third quarter of last year purchases of
goods and services were but 8.1 percent of GNP, compared with more
than 10 percent in the 1960s.
   _The Trade Deficit Isn't Narrowing Fast Enough.
   Really? Says Yardeni: ``The adjustment process is still working
in our view and it will take another two years to produce a zero
trade balance.'' Imports have clearly stopped growing. Exports are
well above previous-year figures.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues., Jan. 10.</NOTE>
</DOC>
