<HEAD>Montserrat: Emerald Isle of the Caribbean</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Montserrat (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This island of 12,000 people has been
British since 1783, but a carved wooden shamrock perches on the
colonial governor's roof and an immigration officer will stamp the
Irish symbol in your passport.
   Montserrat, a pear-shaped haven of densely forested mountains,
palm trees, multicolored flowers and gray-black volcanic beaches
between Antigua and Guadeloupe, is a hint of Ireland in the
Caribbean.
   Tourist brochures call it the Emerald Isle, St. Patrick's Day is
a legal holiday and a version of Irish stew is a local delicacy.
   Although the population is 98 percent black and the climate
semitropical, you can flip through the telephone book and imagine
yourself in Killarney. Row after row of Ryans, Rileys and O'Garros.
   Both the head of government and his main rival are named Osborne:
Chief Minister John and opposition leader Bertrand, a distant cousin.
   Driving around Montserrat, a hilly 11 miles long and seven wide,
you pass St. Patrick's, Cork Hill, Sweeney's Estate, Carr's Bay,
Bransby Point and Galway's Soufriere, a volcanic crater of bubbling
sulfur.
   In the north, you find the most Irish Montserratians of all, the
so-called black Irish, who make up 10 percent of the population and
are as likely as not to speak with a hint of brogue and have a tinge
of red in the hair.
   Most other Montserratians are descendants of slaves who took
their masters' names after emancipation in 1832, when Irish people
greatly outnumbered English on the island.
   Anthropologist John Messenger of Ohio State University said the
black Irish descend directly from legal marriages in the 17th
century between African slaves and Irish plantation owners, and
Irish customs were passed down through the centuries.
   ``They are very close-knit and inbred,'' he said, and three
family names predominate: Gibbons, Sweeney and Allen.
   Among them, Messenger found Montserrat's last known Irish fiddler
a few years ago. ``He held the fiddle in the crook of his arm and
his daughter did an Irish stepdance,'' the anthropologist said.
   Messenger and his wife Betty, a fellow anthropologist at Ohio
State, have been digging at Montserrat's Irish roots since 1965.
They were making their 20th or so visit over the Christmas-New Year
school break and talked about their work.
   Christopher Columbus sighted the island in 1493 and named it for
the serrated mountains and abbey of Montserrat in Spain. The English
settled Montserrat in the early 1600s, and gained undisputed control
in 1783 after a series of wars with the French.
   John Messenger said there is historical evidence the Irish
arrived in two separate groups in the same year, 1632, and settled
on different parts of the island. One contingent came from nearby
St. Kitts and the other from Jamestown in Virginia Colony, both to
escape Protestant persecution, he said.
   Before long, the Irish outnumbered the English on Montserrat.
   They established many of the sugar, lime and tobacco plantations
worked by imported slaves. A census record in 1678 gave the
population as 52 Scots, 761 English, 992 slaves and 1,869 Irish.
   Irish people settled throughout the Caribbean but became
concentrated here.
   Messenger said there was little awareness of the the island's
Irish past until he and his wife wrote several articles for the
Irish Times of Dublin in 1967 and lectured in Ireland.
   Since then, two films on the black Irish have been shown in
Europe and the Irish and Irish-Americans have become interested.
   ``We got the ball rolling,'' the anthropologist said.
   He said the Montserrat tourist industry has promoted the Irish
connection in hopes of attracting Irish-Americans, an estimated
1,500 to 2,000 of whom visited last year.
   Most islanders don't seem all that interested, however. Howard
Fergus, a faculty member at the University of the West Indies and
Montserrat's leading historian, suggested Irishness is not something
they would to boast about.
   ``I don't think there is any attachment to the Irish,'' he said.
``People celebrate St. Patrick's Day here, but apart from the church
connection a number of us celebrate it because on that day there was
a slave rebellion,'' on March 17, 1768.
   About his own name being Irish, Fergus said: ``Yes, but it
doesn't mean anything to me. It merely is a slave name. ... The
Irish are white people.''
</TEXT>
