<HEAD>For release Thursday, Jan. 12, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AIDS Fear Leads To Clotting Factor Shortage For Hemophiliacs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Perhaps the best thing that ever happened to 20,000
Americans with the bleeding disease hemophilia was the discovery of
treatment with a protein called factor VIII. It was also probably
the worst.
   Five-minute infusions of this natural substance overcome their
bodies' inability to form blood clots so they can lead nearly normal
lives. But the price has been disastrously high: The treatments also
have given more than half of them AIDS infections.
   The treatment has been made safe again, but another crisis looms.
Factor VIII is in severe, sometimes life-threateningly short supply.
   ``In the New York region, we've used 30 to 40 percent less
clotting factor'' in 1988, said Dr. Richard Lipton of Long Island
Jewish Medical Center. ``I don't know if I can say anyone has died
because of this, but we have had some pretty hairy situations trying
to find factor VIII for people who are bleeding.''
   Doctors say that because of the shortage, most non-emergency
surgery has been postponed for hemophiliacs. Bleeding often is
treated with less than the recommended doses, sometimes with poor
results. Users have smaller reserves for emergencies. Most have
stopped taking preventive doses and now use clotting factor only for
actual bleeding.
   They also have had to rely more on cryoprecipitate, an older,
less convenient therapy that requires a trip to the hospital to
receive blood plasma that is rich in factor VIII. This treatment
carries the same very slight risk of AIDS as an ordinary blood
transfusion.
   The shortage ``has produced a tremendous amount of frustration,
and in some people despair, in some anger and in some resignation,''
said Donald S. Goldman, a lawyer from West Orange, N.J., who has
hemophilia.
   Hemophiliacs represent just 1 percent of the 80,000 AIDS cases
reported in the United States since 1982. However, a larger
proportion of them are infected than are the other two major risk
groups, homosexual men and drug addicts.
   About 60 percent of U.S. hemophiliacs are infected, and for those
with the most severe form of the disease it's perhaps 80 percent to
90 percent, said Alan Brownstein, executive director of the National
Hemophilia Foundation.
   While most of the hemophiliacs who carry the AIDS virus are still
healthy, doctors fear that many of them will eventually get AIDS.
   Hemophilia is caused by a genetic defect passed from mothers to
sons at conception. Victims don't produce enough factor VIII, one
link in the chemical chain reaction that prompts the body to stop
bleeding. Without treatment, cuts may bleed for days, but the most
common problem is bleeding internally. Bleeding into the joints
causes crippling deformities.
   Once, the only treatment for hemophilia was blood transfusions.
Then blood plasma was substituted. In the 1960s, cryoprecipitate
became the standard. Finally, in the 1970s, factor VIII became
available. Instead of 30 to 50 trips a year to a hospital for
infusions, people with severe cases could quickly treat themselves
at work or at home.
   ``We are talking about people who, aside from the horrible AIDS
tragedy, have been liberated by clotting factor,'' said Brownstein.
``A person with hemophilia can do any job now. If they have a
spontaneous bleeding episode, they can mix their preparations and
infuse themselves on the spot. They can do it as conveniently in a
747 as in their own living room.''
   Factor VIII is derived from human blood. It takes about 30 liters
to produce enough clotting factor for one treatment. In commercial
production, blood plasma from many people is mixed together. A
single dose may contain elements of blood from 20,000 people or more.
   No one knew it at the time, but during late 1970s and early
1980s, AIDS virus in the donated blood passed through the
purification process into the factor VIII. In 1982, the U.S. Centers
for Disease Control reported the first three suspected cases of AIDS
among hemophiliacs.
   In 1984, manufacturers began heating the clotting factor in an
effort to kill HIV, the AIDS virus, and a year later, a test became
available to screen donated blood for the virus. Since then, factor
VIII makers have adopted other cleansing techniques, including
detergents and antibodies.
   Since 1985, only 18 new AIDS infections have been documented,
said Brownstein, who believes the latest strategies have made
clotting factor HIV-free. But they have also made it expensive and
scarce. The new processes yield only about half as much factor VIII
per liter as the earlier techniques.
   Robert W. Reilly, president of the American Blood Resources
Association, an industry group, said the price has risen six- to
seven-fold since 1985. Enough clotting factor for one person now
typically costs about $50,000 a year, Brownstein said.
   The price and supply were also affected by low demand for
albumin. Until recently, factor VIII was simply a by-product of the
business of producing albumin, which was used to restore blood
volume after surgery and burns. However, albumin is being replaced
by newer treatments.
   Factor VII was already in short supply at the start of 1988. But
the situation became much worse because of problems at the American
Red Cross, which produces about 20 percent of the country's clotting
factor.
   Last April, the Red Cross discovered it had allowed factor VIII
to be made from blood that should have been discarded because of
potential AIDS contamination. Dr. S. Gerald Sandler, vice president
for blood services, said that most of this was from people whose
blood twice tested positive for HIV during initial screening but was
shown by later confirmatory tests to be safe.
   These donations were thrown out, but the donors were later
allowed to give blood again. This time their blood passed the
initial screening test. However, because of their earlier positive
results, acceptance of the blood was a violation of Food and Drug
Administration rules.
   Since then, the Red Cross has released little factor VIII,
although it recently resumed production. Meanwhile, about 7 percent
of the nation's usual annual production is on hold. Officials of the
Red Cross and FDA believe it is safe. But because of errors in the
way it was produced, FDA officials say they would be breaking their
rules if they allowed its release.
   Paul Parkman, director of the FDA's Center for Biologics
Evaluation and Research, said the FDA might allow the questionable
factor to be released as an experimental drug. Users would have to
sign consent statements acknowledging that they understood the
protein did not meet federal standards.
   Brownstein said that last year, 675 million units of factor VIII
were available in the United States, and 591 million were used. In
1988, about 450 million units were available, and virtually all of
it was used.
   Reilly said the major commercial makers expect to improve
production during 1989, and with the Red Cross back in business, the
shortage should begin to ease during the second half of 1989.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Jan. 12</NOTE>
