<HEAD>Scientists Trying To Develop Cosmic Dust Catcher For Space Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists are trying to find ways to
catch cosmic dust that could provide clues about the origins of life
and the solar system.
   Complicating the problem is that the dust particles zip through
space at 22,370 mph and ``you must catch them with minimum damage,
sort of like catching a ball with a pillow,'' says Joel Williams of
Los Alamos National Laboratory.
   The particles often are smaller than one-thousandth of an inch
across.
   Williams and colleagues at Los Alamos are evaluating dust
catchers for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration,
which wants one on its proposed space station. The device would look
like a foot-thick wall measuring 10-by-10 feet, and would be in
place up to a year because dust ``hits'' are rare, said scientist
Debra Wrobleski.
   ``Many particles striking the collector would come from comets
and asteroids, and studying their chemical composition and structure
could provide clues about the origin and evolution of the solar
system,'' Los Alamos said. By catching particles from outside the
solar system, scientists can learn if they contain substances that
help form amino acids, the building blocks of life.
   The scientists have found a number of potentially useful
materials among the foams and stacks of superthin metal foils they
evaluated with an electron micropscope and other methods. The
materials include polystyrene foams and gold, aluminum and beryllium
foils.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Geological Survey Publishes Inventory Of Antarctic Glaciers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RESTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Studies of how Earth's climate and Antarctic
ice influence each other will be aided by a newly published
inventory of the icy continent's glaciers, the U.S. Geological
Survey says.
   The 278-page atlas of satellite images of Antarctica is the first
chapter in ``Satellite Image Atlas of Glaciers of the World,'' an
11-chapter volume being prepared by the agency. The complete atlas
will provide a global snapsnot of glaciers as they were photographed
in the 1970s by the Landsat satellite.
   Comparing atlas images with other maps and aerial photographs,
can help scientists determine how the area covered by glaciers
fluctuates due to natural or human-caused warming or cooling, said
geologist Richard S. Williams Jr.
   ``The enormous area of ice concentrated in the glaciers of
Antarctica _ about 5.3 million square miles, including 91 percent of
the total volume of glacier ice on Earth _ influences the
temperature, wind and weather patterns over the entire Earth,'' said
Williams, a co-editor of the atlas project.
   ``Changes in the volume and dynamics of the ice sheet, therefore
may cause global climate changes,'' he said. ``In turn, changes in
the temperature of the planet can affect the volume and dynamics of
the Antarctic ice sheet.''
   ``Satellite Image Atlas of Glaciers of the World _ Antarctica''
may be obtained by sending a $40 check or money order with a request
for USGS Professional Paper 1386-B to Books and Open-Files Reports,
U.S. Geological Survey, Denver Federal Center, Box 25425, Denver,
Colo. 80225. Checks should be made out to Department of the
Interior-USGS.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Improvements In Fat Suction Surgery Safety</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computerized suction pump and monitor
can help surgeons remove the right amount of fat and prevent
dangerously excessive blood loss in patients undergoing cosmetic
liposuction surgery.
   Liposuction is the most common U.S. plastic surgery procedure
done for aesthetic purposes, says the Illinois-based American
Society of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgeons, which published a
study about the pump-monitor in the Journal of Plastic and
Reconstructive Surgery.
   During liposuction, the surgeon inserts a small, blunt-tipped
metal tube into a pocket of fat, commonly in the hips, thighs or
abdomen. A suction pump connected to the tube sucks the fat into a
bottle.
   But even a small amount of blood turns the bottle's contents dark
red, so blood loss is difficult to determine, said Dr. Harvey Lash,
a plastic surgeon at the Palo Alto Medical Foundation and nearby
Stanford University.
   ``The exact determination of blood loss ... is important'' to
prevent shock or anemia, Lash said. ``Guess or estimate may not
allow the precise replacement of blood and fluids needed for the
safety of the patient.''
   Precise measurement of fat removal also helps surgeons suck the
same amount of fat from both sides of the body to give a balanced
appearance.
   The new pump has a color monitor that instantaneously shows the
amount of blood and fat removed. Lash and his colleagues were among
the first to test the device, which was developed by his son,
physician-engineer Bob Lash, and is now being marketed nationally.
   The device monitors fat and blood loss using two electrodes in
the bottle. Fat cells don't transmit electricity, but blood
transmits it well. The device determines the ratio of removed blood
and fat by measuring the amount of electricity that moves from one
electrode to another.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Jan. 12</NOTE>
