<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower On Cancelled Exports, Brazilian Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly
lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade in response to the
cancellation of some U.S. export business and to weekend showers in
the South American soybean belt.
   The Agriculture Department said late Friday that private
exporters had reported cancellations of sales of 240,000 metric tons
of U.S. soybeans for delivery to unknown destinations. Analysts said
the most likely buyer was the Soviet Union, which occasionally is
forced to cancel grain purchases due to limited port space.
   Unexpectedly heavy weekend showers in one of Brazil's most
important soybean growing regions also contributed to the early
selling of soybean futures, analysts said.
   But the weekend was drier in Argentina, a large producer of
soybeans, wheat and corn, which helped limit losses on the U.S.
futures markets, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   ``Argentina is a much bigger exporter of wheat and corn than
Brazil,'' he said.
   Cautious trading is expected this week ahead of Friday's USDA
crop report.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 2{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.46\ a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 1 cent lower with March at $2.88} a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to
2 cents lower with March at $2.41 a bushel; soybeans were 1\ cents
to 3} cents lower with January at $8.15 a bushel.
   Livestock futures were higher while frozen pork-belly futures
were mixed in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .30 cent higher with February at
73.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .20 cent higher
with January at 84.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to .58
cent higher with February at 47.35 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .22 cent lower to .45 cent higher with February at
44.35 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mixed on Friday.
</TEXT>
