<HEAD>London Shares Close with Strong Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculation that an international consortium could
soon launch a hostile takeover bid for Britain's General Electric
Co. PLC gave a strong boost to share prices Monday on the London
Stock Exchange.
   The potential bid, estimated at around 7 billion British pounds,
or about $12.4 billion, would be the largest takeover ever seen on
the London exchange.
   The bid speculation gained force over the weekend when Lazard
Brothers and Co. revealed a company had been formed to devise a
proposal ``which may or may not'' lead to an offer for GEC. Widely
assumed to be part of an eventual bidding group is electronics giant
Plessey Co., itself the target of a 1.7 billion pound ($3 billion)
bid from GEC and West Germany's Siemens AG.
   At the close of trading, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was up 20.2 points, or 1.1 percent, at 1,831.5.
   The index began the day with a gain of 15.2 points, its minimum
level, before rising as much as 24.7 points by around midday.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed with a gain of 20.7
points at 1,502.0. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 11.31
points to close at 1,031.20.
   Volume picked up strongly, as a brisk 589.7 million shares
changed hands, although turnover was concentrated in a handful of
selected stocks. The figure was up from volume of 459.5 million
shares on Friday.
   GEC shares jumped 19 pence (34 cents) to finish at 221 pence
($3.91) in heavy trading. Plessey shares were down 2 pence (4 cents)
at 226 pence ($4) at the close.
</TEXT>
