<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Business, Bjt,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Refuses To Revive Bendectin Lawsuits Against Dow Chemical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a major victory for Dow Chemical Co., the
Supreme Court on Monday upheld a lower court ruling dismissing
hundreds of personal injury lawsuits tied to the chemical giant's
anti-nausea drug Bendectin.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by more than 800
families who filed a federal lawsuit against Merrell Dow
Pharmaceuticals, the Cincinnati-based Dow unit that manufactures the
drug.
   Meanwhile Monday, the justices agreed to decide whether Congress
may outlaw all sexually explicit telephone dial-up message services,
known as dial-a-porn. The high court will rule on the validity of a
1988 law that sought to ban all obscene and indecent messages
available through these services.
   A federal judge in California ruled last summer that the law
could be applied to ban all obscene messages, but he struck down the
law's ban on messages deemed merely indecent.
   The court also made several decisions effecting state and local
governments, including one that bars cities and towns from receiving
$180 million in federal revenue-sharing funds withheld by the Reagan
administration. In the case involving the Dow Chemical subsidiary,
the justices refused to revive lawsuits seeking millions of dollars
in damages on behalf of children with birth defects allegedly caused
by their mothers' use of Bendectin during pregnancy.
   Merrell Dow had agreed in a 1984 settlement to create a $120
million fund to compensate these children, although it did not admit
the drug had caused the defects.
   The settlement later was rejected by a federal appeals court,
which reinstated the suits against Merrell Dow. A federal jury
decided after a 22-day trial in 1985 that Bendectin did not cause
birth defects when taken in prescribed doses.
   That ruling was appealed, and last August it was upheld by the
6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Merrell Dow spokesman William Donaldson said his company was
``pleased with the U.S. Supreme Court's denial of a hearing since
this case is the major case involving Bendectin.'' The company
maintains the drug is safe.
   In other business-related action Monday, the Supreme Court:
   _Left intact a ruling that $180 million in federal
revenue-sharing funds properly was withheld from local governments
under budget cuts imposed by the so-called Gramm-Rudman Act.
   _Agreed to decide whether federal courts should referee some
disputes over electric power rates between public utilities and
local or state regulatory agencies.
   _Refused to bar city-owned water systems from charging some
non-resident customers higher rates than other non-residents even if
there is no cost-related reason.
   _Agreed to decide whether states generally are immune from being
sued for money damages by bankruptcy trustees.
   _Refused to let the government permit Japanese salmon fishermen
off the Alaska coast to use huge nets in which porpoise and other
marine mammals get trapped.
   _Agreed to decide whether the Justice Department must supply a
weekly tax magazine with copies of all federal trial court opinions
and orders in tax cases.
   _Decided to use a dispute over royalties from aerosol valves to
answer a question involving the authority of federal appeals courts.
</TEXT>
