<HEAD>Soybean Futures Fall On Argentine Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply lower Monday
on the Chicago Board of Trade on forecasts for rain in Argentina,
the world's fourth-largest soybean producer, where early growing
conditions have been dry.
   Wheat and corn futures finished mostly higher, although both of
those markets also were pressured late in the trading session by the
Argentine rain forecasts.
   The rain predictions followed a weekend of unexpectedly heavy
showers in Brazil, the world's second-largest soybean producer after
the United States.
   ``This morning the forecasters were saying Argentina would be
relatively dry but later on they started saying there would be more
rain in the next 24 hours in Argentina than was previously
expected,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Further selling of soybean futures was prompted by the
Agriculture Department's announcement late Friday that private
exporters had reported cancellations of sales of 240,000 metric tons
of U.S. soybeans for delivery to unknown destinations.
   ``Everybody assumes it was the Soviet Union that canceled it,''
Lespinasse said.
   At the close of trading, wheat was unchanged to 1{ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in March at $4.48} a bushel; corn was
1} cents lower to { cent higher with March at $2.89\ a bushel; oats
were 3\ cents to 4 cents lower with March at $2.39 a bushel;
soybeans were 2 cents to 12 cents lower with January at $8.06 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
