<FIRST>r f AM-PacificResources     01-09 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pacific Resources,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Officials Cautious About Sale of Pacific Resources</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials reacted cautiously Monday to the
announcement that Pacific Resources Inc., Hawaii's second-largest
publicly held company, has agreed to be bought by Australia's
largest company for nearly $400 million.
   Gov. John Waihee said the state will look closely at the
agreement for Pacific Resources to be merged with Broken Hill
Proprietary Co. Ltd.
   Broken Hill wants to combine its own petroleum exploration and
development business with the refining and marketing operations of
Pacific Resources. The Hawaii company would become its international
headquarters for marketing crude oil.
   The sale must be approved by regulatory agencies, including the
state Public Utilities Commission, and by holders of 75 percent of
Pacific Resources' shares.
   The two companies announced Sunday that their directors have
approved an agreement providing for the merger of Pacific Resources
with a wholly owned subsidiary of Broken Hill, but with Pacific
Resources maintaining its corporate identity.
   Under the agreement, Broken Hill will make a cash tender offer
for all of Pacific Resources' common stock at $19 a share. Pacific
Resources' common shares jumped nearly $5 on the news of the deal,
closing at $18.50 per share in consolidated New York Stock Exchange
trading, up from $13.75 Friday.
   The tender offer is expected to begin this week, with the
transaction completed during the first half of 1989, the companies
said.
   Pacific Resources is a Honolulu-based energy company with
subsidiaries and activities in Hawaii, on the mainland, in Australia
and in Asia. In Hawaii, it operates a refinery and owns the local
gas utility.
   For the first nine months of 1988, Pacific Resources reported
revenues of $674 million and net income of $30 million. It has
assets of $538 million.
   Broken Hill, which was incorporated in 1885, is involved in the
exploration and production of petroleum and minerals and in
steelmaking and related activities.
   In the fiscal year ending last May 31, Broken Hill reported
revenues of more than $9 billion and net income of $790 million.
   The announcement said the board of Alexander &amp; Baldwin Inc., a
Hawaii firm that owns 36 percent of Pacific Resources' common and
preferred shares, has agreed to sell them to Broken Hill at the same
prices being offered to other shareholders.
   Pacific Resources also has granted Broken Hill an option to buy
authorized but unissued common stock equivalent to about 18.5
percent of Pacific Resources' outstanding shares, it said.
   Exercising these two options would give Broken Hill 43 percent of
Pacific Resources' issued and outstanding common shares, the
announcement said.
</TEXT>
