<FIRST>r f AM-NameChanges     01-09 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Name Changes,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Number Of Companies Changed Names In 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More U.S. companies changed their names in 1988
than at any time in the past 19 years, and more than half the
changes resulted from corporate mergers and takeovers, a
corporate-identity firm said Monday.
   The number of companies changing names last year was 1,864, or 6
percent more than the 1,753 that changed names in 1987, the previous
record year, said Anspach Grossman Portugal Inc., which has
conducted an annual survey of corporate name changes for 19 years.
   The number of new names resulting from mergers and acquisitions
last year was 961, or 52 percent of the total, according to the New
York- and San Francisco-based company.
   Among them were Standard Oil Co., whose name was changed to BP
America after its acquisition by British Petroleum Co. PLC; and
Firestone Tire and Rubber Co., whose name was shortened to Firestone
Corp. after the company's sale to Japan's Bridgestone Corp.
   An additional 430 name changes, or 23 percent of the total,
resulted from corporate downsizing, such as spinoffs and
divestitures. Among them were Allegis Corp., the parent company of
United Airlines, which changed its name back to UAL Corp. after
shedding its hotel and car-rental operations.
   Those companies changing their names for reasons other than
mergers or downsizings numbered 473, or 25 percent of the total.
Among theme were James B. Beam Distillers, which changed its name to
Jim Beam Brands Inc., and Deluxe Check Printers, to Deluxe Corp.
   ``Sometimes a company combines well-known names to take advantage
of the equity they have built up among customers,'' said Joel
Portugal, a principal in Anspach Grossman Portugal.
   ``For example, Dr Pepper and Seven-Up merged as Dr
Pepper-Seven-Up; Memorex acquired Telex and became Memorex-Telex;
and Fleet Financial and Norstar Bancorp merged into Fleet-Norstar
Financial.''
   Anspach Grossman Portugal said it compiles its list through
announcements of corporate name changes in newspapers, magazines,
trade publications and other sources. Portugal said there is no one
organization or government agency that keeps track of such changes,
and so his firm's list is an approximation of the actual number of
name changes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
