<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Teledyne     01-09 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Teledyne,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>4th Qtr Earnings Down 38 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Berkley in 4th graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teledyne Inc.'s fourth-quarter earnings fell
more than 38 percent from the same period last year, when investment
sales boosted earnings, the aviation, electronics and insurance
conglomerate said Monday.
   Fourth-quarter earnings totaled $98.2 million, or $8.68 a share,
compared to $158.8 million, or $13.60 per share, during the same
period last year.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose 16.8 percent to $1.25 billion from
$1.07 billion in 1987.
   Profits for all of 1988 rose by about 4 percent to $391.8
million, or $34.03 a share, from $377.2 million, or $32.25 per
share, in 1987.
   For the year, sales rose 8.2 percent to $4.60 billion from $4.25
billion in 1987.
   Berkley Baker, assistant to the president of Teledyne, said the
drop off in the fourth quarter was not from operations.
   ``A year ago, we had sales of investments of $123.4 million. This
year it was just $21.3 million. That's a swing of $102.1 million,''
he said.
   Last year, Teledyne's insurance division sold all of its stock in
a company that was targeted for friendly takeover. A big chunk of
the quarter's $123.4 million in sales of investments came from that
transaction.
   In its earnings report, Teledyne said it was unsure what impact
an indictment against its Teledyne Electronics division in Newbury
Park would have on Teledyne earnings.
   Teledyne Electronics was accused in a 27-count indictment issued
in Alexandria, Va., on Friday of crimes including conspiracy,
bribery and theft of government property. The indictment was the
first issued as part of the Pentagon procurement investigation.
   If convicted, Teledyne faces fines of up to $6.5 million.
   ``We don't think the government has much of a case. We think we
will be acquitted,'' Baker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0339 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-09 0813</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speculators Flee Coffee Futures Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculators bailed out of the coffee futures market Monday in a
frantic, technically inspired sell-off on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp;
Cocoa Exchange although fundamental factors continued to point
toward higher prices.
   On other markets, frozen pork-belly futures plunged; soybean
futures fell sharply; precious metals were mixed; energy futures
rose; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Most coffee futures contracts settled 6 cents a pound lower, the
permitted daily limit for price movement. The limitless contracts
for delivery in March and May settled 9.43 cents and 8.75 cents
lower, respectively, with March finishing at $1.4829 a pound.
   ``What we saw today was a wholesale bailout of speculative
longs,'' or players who previously had bet that prices would rise,
said Kim Badenhop, a coffee-market analyst with Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets Inc.
   Analysts said that after reaching a 27-month high of $1.669 a
pound last Tuesday, profit-taking had brought the coffee market down
by Friday's close to levels that triggered Monday's sell-off.
   The surge in coffee prices during December was rooted in
tight-supply, strong-demand fundamentals, including a drought in the
coffee-growing regions of Brazil and the arrival of winter in the
Northern Hemisphere, the annual peak period for coffee consumption.
   Analysts said those factors remained in place.
   ``The long-term fundamentals suggest we would move to the upside
but it gets kind of scary when you get sell-offs like this,''
Badenhop said.
   Frozen pork bellies for both February and March delivery plunged
the 2-cents-a-pound limit on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
illustrating the market's potential for strong downward moves on
only moderately bearish news.
   The rise in supplies of frozen pork bellies last year to
near-record levels has caused a good deal of consternation among
analysts but has had little impact on prices.
   But Friday's quarterly hogs-and-pigs report from the Agriculture
Department, although by no means an overwhelmingly bearish report,
apparently was enought to trigger Monday's sell-off.
   The report showed a 2 percent increase over the previous year in
the number of pigs that producers expected to be born from December
through February.
   ``The baby pigs born in December, January and February are
slaughtered in June, July and August,'' said Tom Morgan, president
of Sterling Research Corp. in Arlington Heights, Ill. ``If the
December-February farrowings really do go up 2 percent, that means
the summer slaughter will go up 2 percent and that's bearish for the
bellies.''
   Hog and cattle futures finished mixed.
   Live cattle settled .30 cent lower to .20 cent higher with
February at 73.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .62
cent higher with January at 84.97 cents a pound; live hogs were .75
cent lower to .35 cent higher with February at 46.37 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were 2 cents lower to .80 cent higher with
February at 42.45 cents a pound.
   Soybean futures fell as much as 12 cents a bushel on the Chicago
Board of Trade on forecasts for rain in Argentina, the world's
fourth-largest soybean producer, where early growing conditions have
been dry.
   Wheat and corn futures finished mostly higher, although those
markets also were pressured late in the trading session by the
Argentine rain forecasts. Oats ended sharply lower.
   Further selling of soybean futures was prompted by the
Agriculture Department's announcement late Friday that private
exporters had reported cancellations of sales of 240,000 metric tons
of U.S. soybeans for delivery to unknown destinations, which traders
and analysts said probably meant the Soviet Union.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 1{ cents higher with March at $4.48} a
bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to { cent higher with March at
$2.89\ a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 5 cents lower with March at
$2.37} a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 12 cents lower with
January at $8.06{ a bushel.
   Gold and silver futures retreated modestly on New York's
Commodity Exchange in response to the early strength of the dollar,
but platinum futures rebounded on the New York Mercantile Exchange
after the dollar weakened late in the day.
   Gold settled $1.40 to $2.10 lower with February at $406.70 a troy
ounce; silver was 3.2 cents lower across the board with March at
$6.043 a troy ounce; platinum was $10.40 to $10.70 higher with
January at $533.80 a troy ounce.
   In energy trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas
Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 17 cents higher with
February at $17.72 a barrel; heating oil was .34 cent to .59 cent
higher with February at 54.15 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.05 cent lower to .24 cent higher with February at 47.96 cents a
gallon.
   Stock-index futures gained slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 index settled .30 point higher at 283.70. Each point is
worth $500.
</TEXT>
