<FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 1818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Budget-Wrapup     01-09 1266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Wrapup,1322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Highlights Of The President's Budget</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Monday sent Congress a
$1.15 trillion budget that is certain to be changed by
President-elect George Bush and a Democratic-controlled Congress.
   The plan would continue Reagan's legacy of military growth,
squeezed social programs, and optimism that the federal deficit will
disappear without a major tax increase.
   In his proposals for the fiscal year that starts Oct. 1, 1989,
Reagan advocated terminating a total of 82 government programs,
slashing spending on farm programs by $9.7 billion and trimming the
growth in Medicare and Medicaid, the giant health programs, by about
$5 billion. The Pentagon's budget, on the other hand, was awarded a
big spending increase.
   Here is a look at the major items:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MILITARY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's proposed budget would escalate ``Star Wars''
research and move several big-ticket weapons into production, while
sustaining current levels of military forces.
   Reagan requested $315.2 billion in budget authority _ a 2 percent
increase after inflation _ for national defense in fiscal 1990.
   The defense budget envisions that $303 billion of the $315.2
billion will be paid out during the fiscal year. The balance
represents money that would be authorized for various programs but
not spent until later.
   Of the totals, $305.6 billion in budget authority and $293.8
billion in outlays is earmarked for the Defense Department. The
remainder _ $9.6 billion in budget authority and $9.2 billion in
outlays _ is contained in the Energy Department's budget to cover
nuclear warhead production and research work.
   Bush has talked of cutting the request so that it just matches
inflation instead of providing real growth.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HEALTH AND SOCIAL</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan proposed increasing spending for AIDS research and
prevention by 13 percent while reducing the growth of the Medicare
and Medicaid health programs by cutting payments to states,
hospitals and physicians.
   Overall, the budget of the Department of Health and Human
Services _ the largest federal department _ would increase 5.7
percent to $424.4 billion in fiscal 1990. HHS spending accounts for
about 37 percent of the federal budget.
   Medicare and Medicaid have been fueling the growth of the
department's budget.
   President Reagan said his proposed cutbacks would not reduce
benefits to the 56 million elderly, disabled and low-income people
in the two programs, but would force the states, which administer
Medicaid, and providers paid by Medicare to become more efficient
and reduce waste.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDUCATION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush, who promised to be ``the education president,'' will need
to rework this proposal to incorporate his ideas.
   The Reagan plan would eliminate two dozen federal education
programs while slightly increasing overall education outlays from
$20.6 billion this year to $21.2 billion in fiscal 1990.
   Some $541 million saved by the cuts, plus another $212 million
from cost savings officials hope to achieve from the guaranteed
student loan program, would go to expand existing programs for
disadvantaged students from kindergarten to graduate school.
   The Bush ideas not incorporated into this budget include a $500
million merit schools program for schools serving disadvantaged
children and a $50 million infusion for a magnet schools program
designed to encourage parental choice.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FARM</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan wants a 19 percent cut in Agriculture Department spending
in the 1990 fiscal year, including cutbacks in farm commodity
programs and the likelihood of even deeper reductions in the future.
   Other proposed cuts for the fiscal year include spending for
forestry, farm loan programs, community and rural development and
some child nutrition programs.
   Under the proposed budget to operate USDA in the year that will
begin Oct. 1, total spending would be held to $42.4 billion, down
from the estimated outlays of $52.1 billion in the current fiscal
year.
   Spending on the department's Commodity Credit Corp. programs,
which includes wheat, corn and other major crop supports, would
decline to a six-year low of less than $11.6 billion from more than
$13.8 billion in 1989.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WATER PROJECTS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The administration sought funds for 10 new flood control and
navigation projects, including several Congress refused to launch
last year.
   It requested $88.5 million in its fiscal 1990 budget for the Army
Corps of Engineers projects. Six were in last year's Reagan budget,
but Congress refused to start any. The four new projects are in
Ohio, Texas, Pennsylvania and West Virginia.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>VETERANS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Congress was asked to approve a small increase for veterans'
medical care and pensions as the president proposed outlays of $29.9
billion for the new Department of Veterans Affairs.
   Outlays for the Veterans Administration, which provided benefits
and services to veterans for 58 years, are estimated to be $29.2
billion in fiscal 1989.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SPACE AND SCIENCE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The controversial space station program would get $2.1 billion in
spending authority in 1990, along with an extraordinary three-year
advance commitment for billions more.
   The suggested spending limit for the space station during the 12
months beginning Oct. 1 is more than double this fiscal year's limit
of $900 million for building the huge station.
   In general, Reagan's budget is generous to big science,
supporting not only the $16 billion space station but also the $4.4
billion superconducting supercollider proposed by the Department of
Energy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SAVINGS AND LOANS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The savings and loan crisis was dumped into the lap of Bush,
acknowledging for the first time the government does not have enough
money to bail out the troubled industry.
   The administration, in its proposed budget for fiscal year 1990,
outlined plans to spend $64 billion from the Federal Savings and
Loan Insurance Corp., from 1989 through 1994. Of that, $16 billion
would be spent in fiscal 1989, which began last Oct. 1; $9 billion
in 1990, and $39 billion from 1991 through 1994.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NUCLEAR</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan proposed increasing by half a billion dollars the down
payment on modernizing and cleaning up the nation's atomic weapons
complex _ a job expected to cost $81 billion over the next 20 years.
   In his proposed fiscal 1990 budget for the Energy Department,
which makes the nuclear bombs and warheads for the Pentagon, Reagan
asked for $3.014 billion for moderninizing, environmental and safety
programs at the weapons plants. That is $478 million more than is
being spent on them this year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TRANSPORTATION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The administration is proposing $28.2 billion in spending for
fiscal 1990, an increase of some $200 million. Requested funds for
air transportation would increase by about $1 billion, with the
largest chunk going to modernize the air traffic control system.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FOREIGN AID</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The administration asked for $13.2 billion in outlays for foreign
aid, with $3 billion in spending authority earmarked for military
and foreign assistance to Israel, while Egypt was to receive $2.3
billion. For the first time since 1986 the budget also asks for
enough money to cover the entire U.S. contribution to the United
Nations and other international organizations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>JOBS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Outlays for job training and other employment assistance would be
$6.15 million under the 1990 budget, down by $74,000 in the current
year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WHITE HOUSE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan wants to spend $28.5 million for the White House office,
compared to $27.7 million in the current fiscal year. Spending for
the executive residence would be $6.3 million under the plan, down
from $6.5 million in 1989.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CENSUS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   While most federal agencies are struggling with spending cuts or
small increases, the Census Bureau would get nearly triple its
current amount under President Reagan's 1990 budget.
   But don't get too excited, it's only temporary.
   Reagan proposed Census Bureau spending of $1.47 billion for
fiscal 1990, up from about $250 million in 1988 and about $559
million in the current year.
   The reason: the ``decennial'' census.
</TEXT>
