<FIRST>u f AM-MemorexTelex     01-09 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Memorex Telex,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memorex Telex Signs Agreement To Own Half Of National Advanced Systems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Semiconductor Corp. has
agreed to sell half its mainframe computer business to Memorex Telex
NV for $250 million in cash and 4 million shares of Memorex Telex
stock, the companies said Monday.
   National Advanced Systems of Santa Clara, which will become a
joint venture of the two companies, is the largest distributor of
IBM-compatible mainframe computers and data-storage devices made by
Japan's Hitachi Ltd.
   Memorex Telex, based in Amsterdam, is the world's largest
supplier of IBM-compatible equipment such as terminals, data-storage
devices and communications equipment.
   The Dutch company is privately held, so the value of the 4
million shares that National Semiconductor would receive in the deal
is difficult to estimate.
   National Semiconductor's main business other than mainframes is
computer chips. The company said the sale of half of National
Advanced Systems would give it cash for future investment needs and
help the competitiveness of the mainframe unit.
   Under the deal, Memorex Telex would get an option to buy the rest
of National Advanced Systems at a later date.
   ``Even though this is being called a joint venture, I really
don't see that there's much doubt ... of the acquisition of NAS by
Telex somewhere down the road,'' said Bob Djurdjevic, president of
Annex Research Inc., a computer market intelligence firm based in
Phoenix.
   Memorex Telex has annual revenues in excess of $2 billion. It is
made up of the Memorex business, formerly owned by Burroughs Corp.,
and Telex Inc. of Tulsa, Okla. Tulsa remains the U.S. headquarters
of Memorex Telex.
   Djurdjevic said that since Memorex Telex already has a large debt
burden, it made sense for the company to pay partly with stock and
to stretch the expected purchase of NAS over a period of time.
   National Advanced Systems, which has annual revenues of $900
million, will operate as a separate entity with headquarters in
Santa Clara.
   ``This relationship should prove beneficial to both companies and
to our combined customer base,'' said Giorgio Ronchi, president and
chief executive officer of Memorex Telex. ``Through cooperative
programs, we will substantially enhance the worldwide PCM market.''
   Memorex Telex operates in 27 countries worldwide, with
distributor links in another 50 markets. It has some 2,200 employees
worldwide, including 1,200 in the United States.
</TEXT>
