<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration made one final appeal
Monday to spend more for air safety and Coast Guard drug enforcement
while cutting funds for highways, urban mass transit, lightly
traveled airline routes and Amtrak.
   The Department of Transportation's proposed $27.3 billion outlay
for fiscal 1990 contains several familiar refrains, many of which
have met a deaf ear in Congress. One new proposal was for a new ice
breaker after two of four used by the Coast Guard were taken out of
service because of increasing maintenance costs.
   Outgoing Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley, at a news
conference, stressed the budget's proposed increases for aviation,
drug law enforcement and safety programs. But proposed cuts put the
overall total $207 million under fiscal 1989's expenditures.
