<HEAD>Prime Warns Hostile Takeover Could Drive Away Customers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc.'s president told securities
analysts Monday the computer maker's operating income could rise as
much as 50 percent in 1989, but only if it wards off a hostile $970
million takeover bid by MAI Basic Four Inc.
   ``We have received expressions of concern from a number of our
large customers ... about the highly leveraged entity that would
result from a takeover and whether they would still buy from such a
vendor,'' Prime chief executive Anthony Craig said in an interview
after the meeting.
   Wall Street analysts said Craig told them that Prime could lose
$40 million to $100 million in orders if it is acquired by MAI
Basic, a Tustin, Calif.-based computer company controlled by New
York investor Bennett S. LeBow.
   ``It was stated quite harshly, but in terms of the numbers, it
wasn't a fall-off-the-chair impact,'' said Barry Willman, who
follows Prime for Sanford Bernstein &amp; Co.
   Said Willman, ``$40 million to $100 million to my mind isn't that
much, in terms of the corporation,'' which reported sales of $1.16
billion in the first three quarters of 1988.
   Prime stock closed at $19.25, up 12{, on relatively heavy trading
of 580,000 shares.
   MAI Basic spokesman Peter Rosenthal said the firm would not
comment on Craig's remarks.
   A Massachusetts judge temporarily enjoined MAI Basic on Dec. 29
from pursuing its $20-per-share cash tender offer, saying LeBow had
failed to make full disclosure of his financing arrangements with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. But MAI Basic said it would go back to
court this month to submit further information and try to clear the
bid, which totals $970 million.
   Craig said the main purpose of the meeting with analysts was to
``give a good news flash on our expected fourth quarter earnings''
because ``there had been divergent estimates in the absence of
information.''
   The 43-year-old executive, who was named in October to succeed
Joe M. Henson as Prime's president, said fourth-quarter revenue is
expected to increase by 7 percent to 10 percent from $391.4 million
in the prior quarter. Net income is expected to rise more than 40
percent over the third quarter's $11.7 million, he said.
   Craig said Prime has completed its acquisition of General
Electric's Calma subsidiary, giving the company approximately 800
new customers and $60 million to $70 million in revenue in 1989.
   Prime announced Dec. 28 it would eliminate 1,200 jobs in 1989,
bringing its worldwide work force down to about 11,600. The company
also cut 700 employees last year after buying Computervision Inc.
for $435 million.
   Craig said the 1988 restructuring succeeded in rolling back costs
by about $50 million, and that Prime expects to cut costs by a
similar amount again this year.
   He told the analysts he expects a 6 percent to 8 percent increase
in revenue this year and a 10 percent to 12 percent rise in 1990,
primarily because of strong growth in sales of computer-aided design
and manufacturing systems.
   The combination of sharp cost cutting and revenue growth, he
said, could produce a 40 percent to 50 percent increase in operating
income in 1989 and a 20 percent to 30 percent increase in 1990.
