<HEAD>Ford Recalls Heavy Duty Trucks, Sables</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead with 2 grafs to CORRECT that Sables not being recalled
to install omitted parts.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. on Monday recalled about
300 of its 1988 heavy-duty trucks to install parts omitted during
assembly.
   The automaker also recalled about 25,000 of its Mercury Sable
cars to change light bulbs in the vehicles' side marker lamps.
   Ford said in a news release that the trucks, 1988 models of the
F-250 HD four-wheel-drive vehicles, were assembled without fuel
reservoir shields, which are required by federal safety standards.
   The shield protects the fuel tank in a 30-mph front-end crash.
The company said it knew of no accidents, fires or injuries because
of the omission in the trucks, which are more than 8,500 pounds in
gross weight.
   Meantime, the company also recalled 25,000 Sables because a clear
bulb, instead of an amber one, was installed in side marker lamps.
   Owners of the affected vehicles will be notified by mail and
problems will be corrected free of charge, the company said.
</TEXT>
